<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Tower-Thumbnail     12-17 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tower-Thumbnail,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thumbnail Look at Bush's Choice For Defense Secretary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at John Tower, President-elect
Bush's choice for defense secretary.
   AGE: 63.
   EDUCATION: Tower received his undergraduate degree from
Southwestern University in Texas and did graduate work at Southern
Methodist University and the London School of Economics and
Political Science.
   BACKGROUND: The son of a Methodist minister, Tower was in the
Navy during World War II. After the war, he worked as a radio
announcer and insurance salesman before teaching political science
at Midwestern State University in Wichita Falls, Texas.
   CONGRESSIONAL SERVICE: He was narrowly elected to the Senate in
1961, winning a special election to fill the seat vacated by Lyndon
B. Johnson when Johnson became vice president. On the Armed Services
Committee, he made a name for himself as an expert on the details of
weapons systems and defense policy. After Republicans gained control
of the Senate in 1980, Tower became committee chairman. He became
the chief legislative champion of Reagan's defense spending build-up
and a deeply conservative critic of the Soviet Union.
   CONSULTANT: He retired in 1984 to become a high-priced Washington
consultant. In November 1986, Reagan picked Tower as chairman of the
three-man presidential commission investigating the Iran-Contra
affair.
   PERSONAL LIFE: A 1987 divorce from his second wife, Lilla, was
granted after a legal battle in which she alleged that Tower had
committed ``marital misconduct'' and carried on affairs during their
10-year marriage. Tower's deposition responding to the charges was
sealed by agreement of both parties. The Federal Bureau of
Investigation conducted an extensive background check into rumors of
Tower's extramarital affairs and drinking.
</TEXT>
