<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Karate-Kick 1stLd-Writethru a0412 12-17 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Karate-Kick, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0412,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Karate-Kick Killer Convicted of Criminally Negligent Homicide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT `Uviller' to `Wallace'. SUBS last
graf with 2 grafs to include families' reaction to verdict</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted of criminally negligent
homicide Friday in the karate-kick death of another man outside a
bar.
   Robert Wallace, 21, initially indicted on a murder charge in the
death of Daniel Klagsbrun, 25, slumped in his seat when the verdict
was announced after 13 hours of deliberations over two days.
   State Supreme Court Justice Rena Uviller released Wallace on bail
until sentencing Feb. 2. Wallace faces up to four years in prison.
   Wallace was accused of picking a fight with Klagsbrun and his
five companions outside a bar on Jan. 24 after one member of the
group offended Wallace.
   When Klagsbrun told him no one wanted to fight, Wallace spun 360
degrees and delivered a booted kick to Klagsbrun's throat, knocking
him back onto the pavement, according to testimony. Klagsbrun died a
short time later.
   Wallace was arrested two weeks later in San Francisco.
   The judge threw out the murder charge Tuesday, leaving just the
first- and second-degree manslaughter and criminally negligent
homicide charges.
   As the jury foreman announced the verdict, both the victim's
family and Wallace's family burst out crying and Wallace's mother,
Pauline, hugged her son.
   ``It's extremely disappointing,'' Herbert Klagsbrun, the victim's
father, said.
</TEXT>
