<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     12-17 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0851</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Frank Sinatra says he feels like he's on
the right track when he gets to spend time playing with his 250
model trains.
   ``The noise of the trains running and whistling can get pretty
loud, but watching the trains just removes my head from thinking
about work,'' Ol' Blue Eyes said in this weekend's edition of USA
Weekend magazine.
   When Sinatra was an 11-year-old boy growing up in Hoboken, N.J.,
he desperately wanted a train set, ``but I didn't know how my family
could ever afford it,'' Sinatra said.
   ``One day, my mother pawned her fox fur piece to buy my first
train set, a windup engine and an oval track. I never forgot that.
It was probably the only decent thing she had to wear and I was old
enough to understand the sacrifice.''
   So, now, at his Rancho Mirage, Calif., home, Sinatra has an
18-by-30 train station with the 250 model traincars. Five trains can
run simultaneously on independent loops, running through Hoboken or
an Old West town and passing by a New Orleans riverboat with a
billboard announcing a sold-out Sinatra concert.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Kim Basinger, currently starring in
the comedy ``My Stepmother is an Alien,'' has filed for divorce from
her husband of eight years, her attorney said.
   The divorce petition filed in Superior Court on Thursday cited
irreconcilable differences as the reason for the breakup between
Miss Basinger, 35, and artist Ronald A. Britton, said attorney
Michael Balaban on Friday. The couple married on Oct. 12, 1980.
   ``My Stepmother is an Alien'' also stars Dan Aykroyd, who plays a
widowed scientist who falls in love with Miss Basinger, a creature
from space.
   She also has appeared in ``The Natural,'' ``Fool for Love,'' ``9{
Weeks,'' ``Blind Date'' and ``Nadine.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cellist Mstislav Rostropovich, who is of Armenian
descent, gave his first solo concert in Britain in nearly 20 years
in a benefit to raise money for the earthquake victims in his
homeland.
   The audience of about 2,000 stood in silence at Rostropovich's
request at the end of the performance Friday, which included works
by Johann Sebastian Bach and British composer Benjamin Britten.
   Rostropovich, 61, an American citizen, was due to take part in a
second charity concert in London today which Prince Charles planned
to attend.
   At the end of the performance, the Archbishop of Canterbury,
Robert Runcie, paid tribute to the Armenian people for ``their
sufferings, their talents and their achievements.''
   ``We have felt something of all three tonight,'' Runcie said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: St. James's is correct.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lord Nicholas Windsor, whose father the Duke of
Kent is a cousin of Queen Elizabeth II, was arrested for possessing
marijuana but was released without charge after receiving a warning
from Scotland Yard.
   Windsor, 18, was arrested with a friend in London's St. James's
Park near Buckingham Palace on Wednesday night, Scotland Yard said
in a statement Friday.
   The two were taken to a nearby police station where officers
issued a caution _ a formal warning _ about possession of illegal
drugs before allowing them to leave.
   It said they were not charged because the amount of marijuana
involved was small. It did not specify the amount of the drug and
gave no other details.
   But a Scotland Yard spokeswoman, who declined to be named, denied
they were treated leniently simply because Windsor, who is 19th in
line of succession to the throne, is a member of the royal family.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Leon Russell is back home after
his release from a Florida hospital where he had surgery to correct
a cerebrospinal fluid leak, his agent said.
   Russell underwent the procedure at St. Luke's Hospital in
Jacksonville, Fla., said agent Brad Davis on Friday.
   ``He is expected to return to performing in about a month,''
Davis said.
   The 47-year-old pianist-songwriter with flowing silver hair is
known for the hits ``Tightrope,'' ``Lady Blue'' and ``This
Masquerade,'' returned Friday to his home in Nashville.
   Davis said the condition caused Russell some sinus problems.
   ``He's still having headaches but that's about it,'' Davis said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Edward, youngest son of Queen Elizabeth II,
criticized a government move to cut welfare benefits for 16- and
17-year-olds as a threatening blow to young lives.
   The 24-year-old prince said Friday the teen-agers were ``prey to
pimps and (drug) pushers'' and because of a shake-up in welfare
payments ``by accident, I'm sure, their plight is about to get
worse.''
   ``This blow is only one of many which can wreck a young life,''
Edward said in a speech during the presentation of an award to a
London charity group.
   The government on Friday proposed a new law aimed at stopping
unemployment benefits for an estimated 50,000 people who do not
actively seek work.
</TEXT>
