<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SocialSecurity     12-17 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Social Security,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many Who Sought Personalized Benefit Statement Have Not Mailed
Application</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Social Security Commissioner Dorcas R. Hardy
says many of the millions of people who flooded her agency with
phone calls last summer for a new personalized benefit statement
have not yet taken the trouble to complete the application.
   ``More than 6 million people have asked us for the statement. But
only 35 percent of them have sent it back to us,'' Hardy told
reporters Friday. ``It's still hanging on their refrigerators.''
   The Social Security Administration had trouble fielding all the
phone calls requesting its Personal Earnings and Benefit Estimate
Statement (PEBES) when it became available in August.
   But Hardy said the bottleneck on the phone lines has been cleared
and ``we're ready, willing and able to provide them now. I would
really like to have everybody have a PEBES in their stocking.''
   The toll-free number to call is 1-800-234-5772.
   Operators are on hand to answer the calls at various Social
Security centers from 7 a.m. to 7 p.m. local time on weekdays. Those
who call after working hours or on weekends will get a recording
capable of taking messages.
   Once the form is mailed back, it takes the agency three weeks to
crank out the estimates of future monthly retirement benefits, as
well as how much a worker and family gets if he or she becomes
disabled or dies.
   The agency also provides a year-by-year list of workers' wages
and Social Security taxes.
   In other matters, Hardy said she and the Department of Health and
Human Services were unable to get included in President Reagan's
fiscal 1990 budget a proposal to eliminate a Social Security's
earnings test.
   The earnings test reduces benefits of beneficiaries under age 70
who earn more than certain amounts. The thresholds this year are
$8,400 for those ages 65-69 and $6,120 for those under 65; in 1989
they are $8,880 and $6,480 respectively.
   She also said, ``I'm hearing from seniors at town hall meetings
that they are not pleased about the (income tax) surtax that's
coming'' to pay for Medicare's new catastrophic insurance benefit.
   Hardy said she ``wouldn't be surprised'' if Congress took another
look at whether to levy the 15 percent tax surcharge on the elderly
to pay for the insurance, which starts in January.
   Hardy wants all 130 million American workers to request their
earnings records at least once every three years both to ensure
their wages were reported correctly, and to get a better idea of
what to expect from Social Security upon retirement.
   Hardy hopes that people armed with that information will save
more and rely less on the government for their retirement income.
   Currently, more than half the elderly rely on Social Security as
their main source of income. But the program was always intended
just to be part of retirement income, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881217-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 0137EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Koop-DrunkenDriving     12-17 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koop-Drunken Driving,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panels Urges Restrictions On Alcohol Advertising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal panel is calling for restrictions on
alcohol advertising and higher state and federal excise taxes in an
effort to reduce drunken driving by discouraging alcohol consumption.
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop accepted an inch-thick packet of
recommendations Friday at the close of a three-day workshop he
convened, and he vowed to use his high public profile to publicize
the report.
   While stopping short of urging an outright ban of beer, wine and
liquor advertising, the panel said such ads should not be allowed on
college campuses ``since a high proportion of audience reached is
under the legal drinking age.''
   Koop told the workshop participants that his office had little
money or power to implement policy, but promised to provide start-up
funds for a non-profit, private corporation to serve as a
clearinghouse for groups seeking ammunition to use in the war on
drunken driving.
   Koop said that, for his part, he intends to be an aggressive but
not shrill soldier.
   ``I intend to ignore those who would lynch or execute a first
offender in drunk driving just as I will ignore those who would say
it has not yet been proven that alcohol is responsible for impaired
driving,'' Koop told the workshop.
   ``I intend to pursue whatever leadership role I may have between
these two extremes as I have with other issues and to transmit to
that leadership whatever energy, enthusiasm and credibility I have
in this war against impaired driving.''
   The panel's other recommendations called for:
   _Elimination of alcohol advertising and promotion and sponsorship
of public events where the majority of the audience is under the
legal drinking age.
   _Elimination of advertising that portrays activities that are
combined with alcohol use.
   _Banning of sponsorship of athletic events by the alcohol
beverage industry.
   _Blocking the use of celebrities who have a strong appeal to
young people in alcohol advertising and promotion.
   _Requiring that the warning labels Congress recently voted to
require on alcoholic containers also be required to appear clearly
and conspicuously in all alcohol ads.
   No specific monetary figures were contained in the section on
taxes, but the panelist said excise tax rates at both the federal
and state level should be equalized among beer, wine and liquor and
indexed to rise automatically with inflation.
   The advertising section was most controversial, largely because
the National Association of Broadcasters and the advertising
industry had declined to participate in the workshop, claiming it
was stacked against advertisers' interests.
   ``In fact, the research the ad industry provided the panel
demonstrates that there is no existing evidence that links
advertising and alcohol abuse,'' said Howard Bell, president of the
American Advertising Federation in a statement Friday.
   NAB President Edward O. Fritts wrote Koop last month: ``At best,
this workshop is designed to politicize the emotional tragedy of
drunk driving. At worst, it is a total abuse of the policy-setting
process.''
   Koop, who had not responded publicly to that charge, lashed back
at the end of his remarks Friday.
   ``I wanted everyone to hear the NAB's point of view not only
because broadcasters are very influential, but because they also
have so much at stake in this issue,'' he said. ``Hence, they
certainly have the right to be here.''
   Koop said he felt the criticism of the workshop was unfair and
said he was ``taken aback'' by what he called Fritts' ``unfortunate
choice of words.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881217-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 0139EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan     12-17 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says America No Longer The Dominant Global Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said in the last major foreign
policy speech of his presidency that America ``no longer enjoys
preponderant power'' in the world.
   As a result, Reagan said, his Oval Office successors and the
Congress must not treat each other as ``adversaries'' but must work
more cooperatively if the United States is to be successful in
pursuing its interests in the global arena.
   ``It is precisely where Congress and the president have worked
together, as in Afghanistan and Cambodia, or resolved differences,
as in Angola, the Persian Gulf and many aspects of U.S.-Soviet
relations, precisely there, (where) our policies have succeeded, and
we see progress,'' the president on Friday told students and faculty
at the University of Virginia, on the campus founded by Thomas
Jefferson.
   ``But where Congress and the president have engaged each other as
adversaries _ as over Central America _ U.S. policies have faltered
and our common purposes have not been achieved,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan said he thought that Congress in recent years had taken on
too great a role in making foreign policy. Instead of linking his
own support for the Contra rebels to the difficulties in Central
America, Reagan blamed Congress' ``on-again, off-again
indecisiveness on resisting Sandinista tyranny and aggression'' in
Nicaragua for leaving the area ``a region of continuing danger.''
   Reagan complained about the War Powers Resolution, which gives
Congress a veto power over the commitment of U.S. troops abroad
after a 60-day period.
   He lamented attempts by Congress to ``manage complex issues of
foreign policy by the blunt instrument of legislation, such as
unduly restrictive intelligence oversight, limits on arms transfers
and earmarking of 95 percent of our foreign assistance, denying a
president the ability to respond flexibly to rapidly changing
conditions.''
   In his speech, Reagan also lauded Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, saying ``let us credit him'' for his reforms. But Reagan
added that America must remain skeptical about the U.S.-Soviet
relationship because ``serious problems, fundamental differences
remain.''
   ``Yes, we welcome Mr. Gorbachev's recent announcement of a troop
reduction,'' Reagan said, ``but let us remember that the Soviet
preponderance in military power in Europe remains _ an asymmetry
that offends our Jeffersonian senses _ and endangers our future.''
   ``So we must keep our heads, and this means keeping our
skepticism,'' he said.
   He credited Gorbachev with taking ``some daring steps'' to bring
about reforms that Reagan said would have been unthinkable under
former Soviet leaders Josef Stalin, Nikita S. Khrushchev and Leonid
I. Brezhnev.
   The president said the superpowers are ``coming closer'' to
agreement on a Strategic Arms Reduction Talks treaty, saying that
``where the portions of the draft treaty disputed by one side or the
other are put in brackets, we are slowly seeing the brackets
disappear.''
   The president also credited America's ``strong and steadfast''
support of Israel's statehood for persuading the Palestine
Liberation Organization to moderate its views toward the Jewish
nation.
   ``That resolve has now paid off'' with the opening of a U.S.-PLO
dialogue aimed at advancing peace in the Middle East, Reagan said.
   Reagan's speech came in the wake of his decision to reverse a
13-year U.S. policy of refusing to have contact with the PLO.
   ``Where we are strong and steadfast, we succeed,'' he said. ``The
country stood firm for years, insisting that the PLO had to accept
Israel's right to exist ... and renounce terrorism.''
   During a brief question-and-answer session with students, Reagan
called the opening to Yasser Arafat's PLO ``a great step forward.''
But he said that peace will be achieved only ``when the principals
come together to negotiate.''
   White House officials have said Reagan plans a farewell address
to the nation sometime in January _ probably from the Oval Office.
But spokesman Roman Popadiuk said Friday that he did not know of any
other foreign policy addresses scheduled in the remaining 35 days of
Reagan's presidency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881217-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 0140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CasablancaPiano     12-17 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Casablanca Piano,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Casablanca Piano, Oz Witch's Hat Sold At Auction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three of Hollywood's holy relics have changed
hands.
   A piano played by Sam in ``Casablanca,'' the hat worn by the
Wicked Witch of the West in ``The Wizard of Oz'' and Clark Gable's
script for ``Gone With the Wind'' were all sold at auction Friday.
   The Japanese trading company C. Itoh & Co. outbid developer
Donald Trump to buy the piano for $154,000, on behalf of an
anonymous ``Casablanca'' fan in Japan.
   ``It's because many Japanese are fans of the old '40s movies,''
said a company representative, Mashahiro Kanaoka.
   Trump, who was in the audience bidding, went home without comment
immediately after the piano sold at Sotheby's auction house in
Manhattan.
   The green and beige upright piano, used in the flashback sequence
of the 1942-43 Warner Brothers classic, had a pre-sale estimate of
$75,000 to $100,000 by Sotheby's.
   Frankly, a dear price was paid for Gable's script from the 1939
film ``Gone With the Wind'' _ $77,000, bid by telephone by Detroit
disc jockey Dick Purtan. Sotheby's had listed an estimate of $3,000
to $4,000 for the leather-covered script with Gable's name embossed
in bold.
   The auction catalog said Gable gave the script to an MGM studios
secretary who was a ``close personal friend.''
   An anonymous private collector in Australia submitted the winning
bid of $33,000 for the witch's hat. The black pointed hat was all
that remained of the wicked witch when Dorothy accidentally melted
her with a bucket of water.
   Nine stemware glasses from Rick's Cafe Americain in
``Casablanca,'' estimated at $1,000 to $5,000, sold for $3,020. A
Masonite advertising board used at the movie's 1943 premiere,
estimated at $5,000 to $7,000, was sold for $22,000.
   The ``Casablanca'' piano was from the Paris flashback scene at Le
Belle Aurore Cafe, where Rick (Bogart) and Ilsa (Ingrid Bergman)
discuss love, marriage and the impending German occupation while Sam
(Dooley Wilson) plays ``As Time Goes By.''
   Later, Rick and Ilsa meet again at Rick's Cafe in Casablanca,
where Sam plays an encore on another piano.
   ``You played it for her. You can play it for me,'' Rick said. To
which Sam replied, ``But I don't think I can remember.''
   ``If she can stand it, I can. Play it!'' Rick commanded, in a
line that has since been widely misquoted as ``Play it again, Sam.''
   Many famous props, such as the ruby slippers from ``The Wizard of
Oz'' and the sled from ``Citizen Kane'' were made in multiples.
However, ``This piano from the Paris scene is truly unique in that
it was actually used throughout the entire Paris cafe sequence,''
the auction catalog said.
   The piano also was used in 1943 in a U.S. Savings Bond drive
featuring Judy Garland, Mickey Rooney and Lucille Ball.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
