<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     12-17 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FEC Selects McDonald As Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Election Commission has selected
Democratic Commissioner Danny McDonald as its chairman for the
coming year.
   McDonald was appointed to the regulatory panel in 1981 and served
as chairman in 1983. He succeeds Thomas Josefiak, who retains his
seat on the six-member commission. Commissioner Lee Ann Elliott was
selected vice chairman.
   FEC members are presidential appointees, serving six-year terms,
with three Democrats and three Republicans serving at any one time.
   McDonald formerly was general administrator of the Oklahoma
Corporation Commission and secretary and chief clerk of the Tulsa
County Election Board.
   The FEC is charged with regulating the federal election process,
including all congressional and presidential campaigns. The panel
enforces the Federal Election Campaign Act of 1974 which governs
limitations on campaign contributions and spending and requires
public disclosure of campaign finances.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>US, Soviets End Round of Talks on Nuclear Testing Without Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department says U.S. and Soviet
negotiators have reached virtual agreement on ways to measure some
underground nuclear tests, but a final agreement still eludes the
two sides.
   The result is further postponement of possible Senate
ratification of two nuclear test treaties completed more than a
decade ago. The treaties would limit underground blasts to 150
kilotons.
   President Reagan has said he would submit the 1974 accord on
weapons tests and the 1976 agreement on tests for civilian purposes
only if agreement were reached on air-tight procedures to guard
against cheating.
   Reagan has accused the Soviets of carrying out tests that
probably exceeded the permissible ceiling. Some American experts
doubted the Soviets had violated the treaties, which both sides are
supposed to be observing even though the Senate has not approved the
pacts.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Court Upholds NRC On Importing Nuclear Fuel From South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nuclear plant fuel may still be imported to the
United States from South Africa despite anti-apartheid sanctions
enacted by Congress, a federal appeals court has ruled.
   A split three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
here ruled that the petitioners lacked legal standing to challenge
the Nuclear Regulatory Commission's decision to allow continued
importation of uranium hexafluoride from South Africa.
   The NRC's 1987 decision was challenged by seven members of
Congress, four private organizations and two individuals, including
an unemployed uranium miner and an anti-apartheid activist.
   The petitioners had contended that the NRC failed to enforce the
anti-apartheid sanctions passed by Congress in 1986 that forbid
continued importation of South African uranium and uranium oxide.
   The NRC had decided that the sanction law did not ban uranium
hexafluoride, a gas that is used to power nuclear reactors.
</TEXT>
