<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel Bjt   12-17 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, Bjt,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Accuse Radicals Of Trying To Undermine U.S.-PLO Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin accused radical
Palestinians of trying to undermine the U.S.-PLO talks by staging
violent riots in the occupied territories that left at least four
Arabs dead.
   Rabin and other officials refrained from direct comment Friday
after U.S. and PLO delegates held their first face-to-face meeting
in Tunisia, but they reiterated their opposition to Washington's
decision to speak to the organization.
   Rabin said the U.S. decision was ``a grave mistake.''
   ``You abandoned an important principle in the general American
policy, the principle of opposing terrorism and waging war against
it,'' he said on Israel Television.
   Rabin spoke after the 90-minute meeting between U.S. Ambassador
Robert H. Pelletreau and a four-man PLO delegation in Carthage, a
suburb of the capital city Tunis.
   The defense minister said Israel should demand the United States
make Arafat prove he was sincere when he said last week that he
renounced all forms of terrorism.
   ``Our first demand from the United States should be, put Arafat
to a test, demand from him to come out and tell all the Palestinians
in his voice, in Arabic, to stop terror,'' Rabin said.
   Despite his opposition to the American-PLO dialogue, Rabin said
it could lead to a decrease in violence.
   ``It was clear to us that a large part of the (Palestinian)
population will see the events of the week as their achievement, and
will try to moderate their role in violence,'' he said.
   ``But it was also clear that radical elements who oppose these
moves ... will try to heat up the area,'' Rabin told Israel
Television.
   Rabin, the No. 2 man in the left-leaning Labor Party headed by
Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, echoed his party leader in saying
Israel should counter the U.S. initiative with its own peace plan,
``even if it would not be accepted in the foreseeable future.''
   He spoke on one of the bloodiest days of the Palestinian
rebellion against Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In Friday's clashes, Israeli soldiers shot to death four Arabs,
and Arab doctors said as many as 32 were wounded.It was among the
worst violence since April 16, when Israeli troops killed 14
Palestinians during riots protesting the assassination in Tunisia of
Khalil Wazir, the PLO military commander.
   The latest deaths brought to 328 the number of Palestinians
killed in the yearlong revolt. Thirteen Israelis have also died
during the unrest.
   Meanwhile, aides to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said the
rightist Likud bloc leader recognized the need for a credible
Israeli peace plan.
   Avi Pazner, Shamir's spokesman, said the prime minister was
considering ``new moves.''
   ``Be sure that Mr. Shamir is preparing a peace move which will
surprise everyone,'' Pazner said, refusing to disclose details.
   Newspaper reports said the plan was to unilaterally establish a
limited self-rule for Palestinians, as envisioned in the Camp David
accords mediated by the United States in 1978.
   Friday's confrontations in the occupied lands were inspired by
the death Thursday night of a teen-ager from a gunshot wound
suffered Nov. 25, according to doctors at Anglican Hospital in
Nablus.
   Army officials said the riots appeared premeditated and began in
numerous areas even before the teen-ager's funeral in the West Bank
city of Nablus.
   West Bank commander Brig. Gen. Gabi Ofir said the high casualty
toll ``resulted from the fact that we had to disperse riots in many
locations.''
   Doctors said 20 people were wounded in Nablus, four of them
critically. The army confirmed four killed and nine wounded.
   Soldiers wounded five Palestinians in villages near Tulkarem in
the West Bank, including a 9-year-old boy shot in the neck, Arab
witnesses said.
   Doctors said seven young men were wounded at the Rafah, Nuseirat
and Jabaliya refugee camps in the Gaza Strip.
</TEXT>
