<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Indonesia-EastTimor     12-17 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indonesia-East Timor,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Timor To Be Opened Up To Outsiders</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rudini uses only one name.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former Portuguese colony of East
Timor will be opened to outsiders by Christmas, officials said.
   East Timor has been closed to foreigners since Indonesian troops
invaded the small island territory in 1975 following an outbreak of
strife between rival nationalist movements and the end of Portuguese
rule.
   International humanitarian organizations estimate as many as
100,000 people, one-sixth of East Timor's population, may have died
in the hostilities and from the disease and famine that ensued.
   Indonesia subsequently annexed East Timor as its 27th province.
Since then, people traveling to and from the territory have needed
certificates issued by security authorities.
   The home affairs minister, Rudini, said Friday that the security
situation in the area had improved, allowing a relaxation of
controls.
   International groups have called repeatedly on Jakarta to allow
humanitarian organizations into East Timor to observe the human
rights situation.
   The U.N. General Assembly also has called on Indonesia to
withdraw and allow residents of East Timor to determine their own
future. Nationalist guerrillas on the island continue to resist
Indonesian rule.
</TEXT>
