<HEAD>Former Military Strongman Released From Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former strongman Gen. Muhammadu Buhari has
been released from prison, three years after he was toppled by a
coup, the military government announced.
   Duro Onabule, spokesman for the Armed Forces Ruling Council, said
Friday that Maj. Gen. Tunde Idiagbon, No. 2 man in the Buhari
government, also had been freed.
   The state Daily Times newspaper said Buhari was seen Thursday in
his hometown, one day after his mother died at age 106 in a village
in the northern state of Katsina.
   The Daily Times said Buhari was greeted by his family and
hundreds of villagers who treked to his country home to catch a
glimpse of the former leader.
   Officials of the Armed Forces Ruling Council had earlier
indicated Buhari would be freed.
   Buhari overthrew the civilian government President Shehu Shagari
on Dec. 31, 1983. Buhari himself was overthrown on Aug. 27, 1985,
after a 20-month authoritarian rule that included the repression of
journalists, union and student leaders and professional groups.
   President Gen. Ibrahim Babangida has promised to return the
country to civilian rule by 1991.
