<HEAD>Three Irish U.N. Soldiers Rescued By Shiite Militia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mainstream Shiite Moslem Amal militia
today rescued three Irish soldiers serving with the U.N.
peacekeeping force in Lebanon, police said. They were kidnapped a
day earlier by pro-Iranian guerrillas in south Lebanon.
   A police spokesman said Amal also captured 22 Shiite zealots who
were behind the abduction.
   The spokesman said the three were rescued from a house in
Sultaniyeh, a village one mile outside Tbinin, the headquarters of
the 620-strong Irish battallion serving with the U.N. Interim Force
in Lebanon and from where the three were snatched.
   ``The three Irish soldiers are in good shape. They are in Amal
hands now and will be turned over to the Irish command soon,'' said
the spokesman who cannot be named under police regulations.
   There were no other details immediately available.
