<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 0335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChurchClosings Bjt   12-17 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Church Closings, Bjt,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Says Foes of Church Closings Promote `Plantation
Mentality'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Edmund Szoka said a plan to close or
merge 43 inner-city Roman Catholic parishes is needed to erase a
``plantation mentality'' in which white pastors and lay people run
churches attended mostly by blacks.
   The plan, which would entail the largest church closing in U.S.
Roman Catholic history, has angered members of the city's 112
Catholic churches since it was announced in September.
   The cardinal strongly defended the plan in a just-released
transcript of a Dec. 3 meeting of leaders of the Archdiocese of
Detroit, which covers southeastern Michigan and has 1.5 million
members under Szoka's leadership.
   ``I know what I am doing and I believe that I am following God's
will,'' Szoka said in the transcript. ``They can lambaste me all
they want, but my purpose is to fulfill the gospel, to make it
possible for that gospel to be preached effectively to the people
who are here now.''
   Opponents of the closings, who include both black and white
parishioners, picketed outside Szoka's home Friday.
   The number of Catholics in Detroit has decreased drastically as
whites have fled the nation's sixth-largest city for the suburbs. In
1976, more than 100,000 Catholic households were in Detroit, as
against fewer than 50,000 now.
   About two-thirds of the city's 1.1 million residents are black,
and the vast majority of church-affiliated blacks are Protestant.
   Szoka said the plan, which targets parishes that are losing
membership and are not considered economically viable, will help
deal with the complaints of black Catholics that predominantly black
parishes are led by whites.
   ``Black Catholics tell me that they no longer want the plantation
mentality,'' the cardinal said. ``They don't want this white pastor
saying, `Now you leave my black people alone, I'll take care of
their needs.'
   ``We have the anomaly today of parishes which are predominantly
black with a white pastor and a totally white staff. Why shouldn't
these black people have the leadership in that parish? Why should we
be importing people from the suburbs, white people, to come in here
and continue to run these parishes?''
   Surveys found that 95 percent of the city's churches had strong
black membership, but the operational structure was white, Auxiliary
Bishop Patrick Cooney said Friday.
   ``We're not denying the value of what any white priest, sisters
or brothers have done in the city. But sometime we have to stop and
see what's best for the church and say, hey, it's time for black
Catholic leaders to be seen and heard,'' Cooney said.
   But the Rev. Norman Thomas, pastor of Sacred Heart Church in
Detroit and leader of the Detroit Catholic Pastoral Alliance, a
group fighting the plan, said the assessment was distorted.
   ``We run our own parish here,'' said Thomas, a white pastor,
whose church staff members are mostly black residents of Detroit.
``I think (Szoka) wants to do the right thing but he's being fed
some very bad information and really is speaking with no experience
on these things.''
   Cooney, who has spent five years overseeing the study of urban
churches, said he will deliver recommendations from appeal hearings
on the closings to Szoka on Monday. The cardinal is expected to make
a final decision during the first week in January.
   The archdiocese also released a letter of resignation Friday from
a member of the Implementation Committee, one of two panels formed
to help Cooney judge the viability of urban churches.
   Sister Mary Kelly said in the letter that she believes the board
will recommend closing churches that proved they were healthy in
appeal hearings.
   ``Many parishes slated to close have in fact demonstrated
viability in ways that could be models for other parishes,'' she
said.
   Under the plan, 42 churches in Detroit and one in nearby River
Rouge would close or merge with other parishes. Archdiocese
officials held a series of hearings for parishes wishing to appeal
the closings.
</TEXT>
