<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GrummanLayoffs     12-17 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grumman Layoffs,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grumman Corp. Announces Massive Layoffs To Begin In January</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHPAGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cancellation of a Navy bomber project
has prompted the Grumman Corp. to eliminate 3,100 jobs, but two
congressmen whose region will be most affected promise to fight the
government decision.
   The company announced the layoffs Friday in the wake of the
Navy's decision to scrap the A-6G bomber in the 1990 budget, said
Grumman spokesman Bob Harwood.
   ``This is quite a parting shot from the Reagan administration, an
administration that says it is committed to a strong defense,'' said
Rep. George Hochbrueckner, D-N.Y.
   Rep. Thomas Downey, D-N.Y., called the Navy's decision
shortsighted.
   Both men vowed to fight to reverse the decision or to get
additional work for Grumman to avoid further cuts.
   Of the 3,100 jobs, 2,500 are from the company's operations on New
York's Long Island. The remaining 600 will be in Florida, Georgia
and Maryland.
   ``Our whole industry is facing flat or declining budgets,'' said
Grumman Chairman John O'Brien.
   A special edition of the company newspaper Friday morning carried
word of the layoffs, which begin next month.
   ``We know it is unfair to tell them at Christmas but it would be
unfair not to let them know what may be coming,'' said Harwood.
   The A-6G would have incorporated advanced digital electronics,
satellite navigation capability and a more powerful engine.
   Grumman has been building the A-6 since the early 1960s,
upgrading it several times over the years. The A-6G, an upgraded
version of the bomber, would have generated 1,000 new engineering
positions and brought in $250 million annually.
   In the past two years Grumman has been bumped from three major
military aircraft contracts. A contract to produce the Navy's
Advanced Tactical Aircraft, the replacement for the A-6, was awarded
to McDonnell Douglas and General Dynamics in 1987, and the company
also lost out in the bidding for the Air Force's Advanced Tactical
Fighter.
   Grumman was at its peak in the late 1960s when it was building
lunar modules and employed 40,000 workers. The company now employs
32,000 workers.
   About 1,800 of the Long Island layoffs will occur in January, and
the rest will come by the end of 1989. Grumman had announced layoffs
in January 1987 and last March.
</TEXT>
