<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CarmelTraffic     12-17 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carmel Traffic,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carmel Highway 1 Bypass Voted By Coastal Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARMEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A traffic gridlock at picturesque Carmel
along Highway 1 will be history if the California Coastal Commission
gets its way.
   The panel has given preliminary approval to a $25 million bypass
through a prized forest of old pines and oaks.
   Other agencies that would have to approve the bypass include the
U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, the state Department of Fish
and Game, the Army Corps of Engineers, and Monterey County planners.
   The 11-0 vote Thursday has state highway engineers hoping they
can ease a bottleneck on the state's 1,000-mile coastal Highway 1
that results from traffic turning into Carmel's Ocean Avenue. The
traffic can stretch as far as five miles without moving.
   ``Carmel will never be the same after the first tree falls'' in
Hatton Canyon, warned Sally McPhail, a resident of the often
tourist-choked seaside town where actor Clint Eastwood served as
mayor.
   The town nestles close to the Pacific, 120 miles south of San
Francisco and just south of the Pebble Beach Golf Course. It is
populated by the wealthy and a colony of artists and writers.
   Called the Hatton Canyon freeway project, the four-mile Monterey
Peninsula bypass would run inland from Highway 1, on the north edge
of Carmel, through large virgin stands of Monterey pines and native
live oaks, across the mouth of Carmel Valley to the east, then back
to Highway 1 on the south edge of town.
   During the three-hour meeting, commissioners heard nearly 40
witnesses, most of them opposed to the project.
   In proxy statements, Monterey Peninsula legislators approved the
project. And Monterey County Supervisor Sam Karras told the
commission the bypass was ``crucially needed ... if we don't get on
with the project, there will be severe safety consequences.''
   One prominent exception to the nearly solid governmental support
for the Hatton Canyon project was Carmel Mayor Jean Grace. She said
there were strong objections to a ``Los Angeles-style interchange''
she said would be built at the north end of the bypass.
   ``This roadway should lie gentle on the land,'' she said, echoing
a sentiment expressed in a letter by her predecessor, Eastwood.
   The issue of a Highway 1 traffic relief dates back to the 1950s.
</TEXT>
