<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 0409EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NuclearWaste Bjt   12-17 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Waste, Bjt,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governors, Energy Department Lay Groundwork For Solving Nuclear
Waste Impasse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department should be able to
meet conditions set by three governors for resolving a deadlock over
the storage of radioactive waste from nuclear weapons plants, a
department official said.
   The governors of Idaho, Colorado and New Mexico emerged from a
private meeting Friday with pledges of cooperation from Deputy
Energy Secretary Joseph Salgado.
   ``I think we've laid a solid groundwork for progress. We've put a
process in place. ... I believe it will bear fruit,'' Salgado said.
   But the governors said they would continue to pressure the
government to make sure the Energy Department honors its promise to
hasten the opening of the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant, a prototype
storage facility under construction near Carlsbad, N.M.
   ``We stand here today to say there is no way we can guarantee
anything. There are uncertainties in the world, but I think we can
bridge that,'' said Colorado Gov. Roy Romer following the three-hour
meeting.
   The officials announced progress toward resolving the most
immediate problem, triggered when Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus closed his
state's borders to waste shipments in October to try to force the
Energy Department into action.
   Andrus said he would reconsider his decision if the Energy
Department speeded up the New Mexico plant's opening. His decision
is expected next month.
   Andrus said he decided to reconsider after being told in a
classified briefing that his ban on waste shipments into Idaho could
harm national security by forcing closure of the Rocky Flats nuclear
weapons plant near Denver.
   Since Andrus' order, the material has been piling up at Rocky
Flats, which manufactures plutonium triggers for nuclear warheads.
   Romer has said he would close the plant when its temporary
storage capacity is filled. That should occur between March and May.
   After the meeting, however, Romer said he doesn't anticipate
closing the facility, although ``I cannot work with additional
storage in a metropolitan area of 1.5 million people.''
   Waste is being stored temporarily at the Idaho National
Engineering Laboratory in eastern Idaho until the New Mexico plant
opens, which Salgado said probably won't be until November or
December 1989.
   The plant, originally scheduled to open last fall, will store
wastes, including equipment and clothing that has been contaminated
during the weapons-making process, in salt deposits more than 2,000
feet underground.
   Andrus said that before he allows shipments to the Idaho plant to
resume, the Energy Department must also keep its pledge to introduce
legislation and begin administrative procedures for a land swap with
the Interior Department that must be completed before the pilot
plant can open.
   The department also must prepare plans to remove the more than 4
million cubic feet of radioactive waste already stored in Idaho.
   ``I said I wouldn't accept that old statement of `trust me.' I
said, `show me,''' said Andrus. ``I said, `If you're sincere, come
back and prove it to me in January and we'll reconsider.'''
   Salgado said the department would appoint a task force to look
for other temporary waste storage sites in case Andrus refuses to
lift his ban.
   But he expressed confidence that the necessary conditions could
be met to continue operations at Rocky Flats and move forward with
the opening of the pilot plant.
   One of the biggest stumbling blocks has been Congress' failure to
pass a bill to transfer several thousand acres of land around the
New Mexico plant from Interior Department control to the Energy
Department.
   The opening also has been delayed because of lapses in
engineering assessments and questions about water leakage at the
site.
   Salgado said the department will have a bill introduced when
Congress convenes in January. The department also will start
administrative procedures for the exchange should Congress move too
slowly, he said.
   ``Clearly, I think the DOE is trying to turn up the heat,'' New
Mexico Gov. Garrey Carruthers said at a news conference in Santa Fe,
N.M., upon his return from Utah.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
