<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Quake-Homeless 1stLd-Writethru   12-17 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quake-Homeless, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0421,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anxious Armenian Villagers Await Rebuilding Of Town</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS 16 grafs to UPDATE with rescue of 21 people, search to
continue for survivors. Picks up graf 17 pvs, `George Reid ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUSAKHPYUR, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The glow from an oil lamp illuminated
the faces of the Armenian villagers who came in from the snow to
visit the mayor in the plastic hut he and his family have lived in
since the Dec. 7 earthquake.
   The mayor, Napoleon Megerditchyan, who was pinned under a block
of stone for several hours until his son rescued him, reassured the
men of the village that their mountainside homes would be rebuilt
within two years.
   ``Gorbachev said he will do something, and he will,''
Megerditchyan said, referring to Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, who toured the disaster area last week.
   In the meantime, authorities are faced with finding winter
shelter for the estimated 500,000 survivors of one of the century's
worst quakes.
   The one-room corrugated shack, thrown up immediately after the
earthquake with supplies from the Red Cross, is cool already, and
will offer scant protection when temperatures drop further this
winter.
   Throughout the region, Armenians are preparing to endure the
approaching Soviet winter and recover from the shock of an
earthquake that killed at least 55,000 people.
   In Lusakhpyur, about 600 of the 1,000 residents already have left
seeking warmth in the homes of friends and relatives who survived
the quake. Seventy villagers were killed, including 50 children
crushed in a grade school corridor as they ran from collapsing
classrooms.
   Ice-covered mountain roads connecting northwestern Armenian
villages were bumper to bumper Thursday with cars, buses and trucks,
listing under the weight of refugees and their few belongings.
   Soviet military trucks with supplies of bread, milk, meat, heavy
coats and boots struggled through the traffic to deliver supplies to
the needy. People generally did not appear hungry or in need of warm
clothes, although some complained the emergency rations weren't
being distributed fairly.
   ``They select those they want to give to, and there is a
hierarchy,'' said Asat Petzosyan of Spitak, a city of about 25,000
almost wiped out by the quake. Officials say about 15,000 died in
Spitak.
   ``I need somewhere to sleep,'' Petzosyan said, rubbing hands
scarred from digging through the rubble searching for family and
friends. ``All I have been given is this coat.''
   Petzosyan and his neighbors have gathered pieces of broken
furniture and torn mattresses to create living rooms without walls
around outdoor bonfires, their only protection against the icy wind.
   Down the street, an elderly man stood motionless, surrounded by
the roar of bulldozers, staring into a heap of rubble two-stories
high. Tears ran down his unshaven cheeks.
   ``My granddaughter is in there,'' he said faintly. ``She is four.
I'm waiting for her.''
   But a happy ending is unlikely. Soviet authorities, fearing the
spread of disease from decaying bodies, began razing Spitak on
Friday.
   Later, workers rescued 21 people from the ruins in Spitak and
Leninakan, prompting authorities to extend their search for possible
survivors.
   George Reid, a spokesman for the League of Red Cross and Red
Crescent Societies, said the greatest challenge now is providing
shelter for those who remain. ``It is a terrible dilemma of
conflicting needs _ the need for sanitation and the feelings of
relatives,'' he said.
   ``Officials say they will evacuate 70,000 people, but that leaves
430,000 without homes,'' Reid said. ``Where do you put 430,000
people for the winter?''
   The Red Cross is bringing in 5,000 winter tents like those
already delivered by the Norwegian army.
   And Soviet authorities are hoping to bring in by rail thousands
of yurts, versions of the circular tents used for centuries on the
frigid steppes of Central Asia. Soviet soldiers are working beside
civilian crews to quickly repair the rail lines just outside Spitak.
   Soviet officials also hope to bring in thousands of mobile homes
for the local men who will be rebuilding their town.
   Azen Akopyan, a worker at an elevator factory, will stay in the
mobile home camp near Spitak. His wife, Nina, will join her children
next week at a temporary shelter set up by his trade union to house
survivors.
   ``I don't want to leave until Azen is in a warm place, but I wish
they would hurry,'' said Mrs. Akopyan, one of the few women in town
who did not lose a member of her immediate family. ``When they
rebuild Spitak, I guess I'll be back. But really, after all this, I
am so afraid of the mountains.''
</TEXT>
