<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-MysteryCrash     12-17 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Mystery Crash,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lear Jet Overshoots Destination, Crashes In Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lear Jet flying from Tennessee to
Texas mysteriously overflew its destination and crashed in rugged
mountains of northern Mexico with two people aboard, officials said.
   Police spokesman Fernando Campos of Torreon said the search for
the plane was called off Friday because of darkness and rough
terrain and would resume today, with the help of a farmer who
reported seeing the downed plane and two bodies.
   The jet, which left Memphis, Tenn., at about 5 a.m. Friday,
crashed two or three hours later in a mountainous region 100 miles
northwest of Monterrey, according to the Federal Aviation
Administration and the U.S. Embassy in Mexico City.
   The plane had a flight plan for Addison Airport in the Texas
suburb north of Dallas, said Stephen Telkins, embassy press attache.
   An F-16 and another plane tried to intercept and contact the
jet's pilot after the plane overshot its destination, but the pilot
did not respond, the FAA said.
   Araceli Suarez, a police spokeswoman in Monclova, 120 miles
outside Monterrey, said authorities reported a small plane was seen
early Friday and appeared in trouble, possibly low on fuel.
   ``Then they lost contact,'' Ms. Suarez said by telephone. ``It
appears to be a foreign plane.''
   Ms. Suarez said authorities immediately dispatched police units
and a helicopter to search the area.
   The co-pilot was Susan Reynolds, 25, of Dallas, according to the
craft's owner, Roger Crownrich. The name of the pilot was not
immediately known.
   Crownrich, who owns Crownrich Construction Management Inc. in
Dallas, said the jet was used for his business most of the time but
was on a charter run at the time of the crash.
   Ms. Reynolds and a pilot routinely flew to Memphis to pick up
Federal Express packages for delivery, he said. But Crownrich said
the regular pilot was not aboard the latest flight.
   ``It came as a bolt of lighting to me,'' said Crownrich. ``I flew
the plane yesterday to Detroit and it was just purring like a
kitten'' at up to 45,000 feet, which is its normal flying altitude.
   He said something could have happened to the plane's occupants or
the craft could have been sabotaged.
   ``It is pretty obvious that the plane was performing well and was
bound to be on auto pilot, and it flew that course on until fuel
starvation,'' he said. ``But why the pilot and co-pilot were not
able to talk to the flight service is beyond me.''
</TEXT>
