<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Extradition     12-17 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Extradition,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accused American High-Tech Smuggler Loses Round Of Legal Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Accused American high-tech
smuggler Charles McVey lost another round in his complex legal
battle to avoid extradition to the United States.
   McVey failed Friday to win an appeal after three days of
arguments before the British Columbia Supreme Court.
   The U.S. government is attempting to extradite McVey, 63, to face
charges of selling classified high-technology computer equipment to
the Soviet Union.
   However, there have been a series of legal battles and appeals in
the case that started when McVey was arrested in August 1987 while
on a fishing trip to the Yukon.
   McVey, being held in Vancouver, was indicted in 1983 by the U.S.
government on conspiracy-related charges in connection with the
shipment of computer equipment to the Soviet Union from four
computer shops he owned in Anaheim, Calif.
   McVey has denied he was part of a scheme to defraud the
California-based Saxpy Computer Corp. of proprietary rights to its
super computer.
   The legal action Friday related to an Aug. 5 order by Justice
Alan MacDonell that McVey be extradited. MacDonell had ruled he
believed there was sufficient evidence to try McKey on charges of
defrauding the defunct computer company.
   McVey's lawyer, Robert Anderson, argued this week for a habeas
corpus application that was in effect an appeal of the MacDonell
decision.
   Anderson said Friday he intends now to appeal the case before the
British Columbia Court of Appeal.
</TEXT>
