<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HousingViolence     12-17 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Housing Violence,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Service Calls at Tough Atlanta Housing Projected Resumed by Phone
Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Bell has reversed a decision to limit
installations and repairs at four crime-riddled public housing
projects, one of which is so violent that letter carriers get police
escorts.
   The phone company had scaled back service in Bankhead Courts and
the Englewood, Gilbert Gardens and Jonesboro South apartments after
a female technician was harassed at Gilbert Gardens by six men who
accused her of being a police officer. One man drew a gun while the
others rifled her van.
   The woman was released when the resident whose phone she had
repaired came outside and vouched for her, phone company spokesman
Doug Kendig said.
   The company had restricted service calls to Monday mornings,
except for emergencies, and only allowed workers to enter the
projects in groups.
   Southern Bell officials announced Friday that they were changing
that policy and said they had scheduled a meeting Monday with Police
Chief Morris Redding to discuss security precautions.
   The Bankhead Courts housing project has a reputation for danger.
Crime statistics on the project itself were unavailable, but the
Zone 1 police precinct, which covers the 25 square miles
encompassing the project, reported 41 homicides, 122 rapes and 609
robberies in 1987, said police spokeswoman Myrna May. In October
1988, the zone reported six homicides, 16 rapes and 145 robberies,
she said.
   Mayor Andrew Young had condemned the phone service cutback, and
Atlanta Housing Authority spokeswoman Cynthia Hoke said that the
authority was ``outraged'' by it.
   Postal officials suspended service in the project for one day,
after shots were fired near a letter carrier Dec. 10. City officials
criticized the move, and service to the 500-unit complex resumed
Wednesday under police escort.
   Kendig said the initial decision to restrict service calls
resulted because ``we've had folks flash guns and pull knives on our
installers, and threaten to use explosives on our vans.''
   The service restrictions were the latest events in the Bankhead
Courts crime drama, which police officials say has been violent and
drug-ridden for most of its 19 years.
   Four police officers were injured there while making arrests in a
Nov. 5 drug sweep that led to the arrest of 12 residents. A Nov. 10
raid, by 37 officers, led to 27 arrests _ nine on drug charges and
18 for traffic violations and other charges.
   A 24-year-old woman, who journeyed into the complex with friends,
was killed Nov. 3 when a drug dealer, fearing undercover police
officers, opened fire on her car as it approached with its
headlights off.
</TEXT>
