<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 0844EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sweden-Palme     12-17 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweden-Palme,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palme's Widow Agrees to Identification Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA JANZON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of Prime Minister Olof Palme
has agreed to try to identify a 41-year-old Swede being held in the
investigation of her husband's assassination, a newspaper reported
today.
   Christer Pettersson, who was arrested Wednesday, pleaded innocent
Friday in a preliminary hearing, but a judge ruled there were
reasonable grounds to suspect he killed Palme and ordered him held
for further investigation.
   Palme, the dominant figure in Swedish politics for more than a
decade, was killed Feb. 28, 1986 while walking home unguarded from a
downtown movie theater with his wife Lisbet. Mrs. Palme was grazed
by a bullet in the shooting, which took place at close range.
   The Expressen newspaper said Mrs. Palme was willing to try to
identify the suspect but that it remained unclear whether she would
be summoned to do so.
   ``We would like to spare her as long as possible,'' the newspaper
quoted a source close to the investigation as saying. ``If we can do
without her testimony we will try to do that.''
   In another development, prosecutor Jorgen Almblad complained
about the publication of Pettersson's picture in foreign newspapers,
saying that would complicate the case.
   ``If a witness says he has seen the photograph of a suspect in
the paper, the value of the evidence will be rather low at a
confrontation,'' Almblad said on Swedish Radio.
   Several witnesses have identified Pettersson as the man seen
standing outside the movie theater before the Palmes emerged, press
reports said Saturday. But no evidence has emerged that he was the
gunman.
   The killer followed the couple down the street for several blocks
before the shooting, then escaped down a dark alley.
   Sweden's press and libel regulations prohibit publication in this
country of the names and pictures of suspects in criminal cases, in
some instances even after a person has been convicted.
   However, personal information about Swedes is easily available
from various national offices. Since his arrest, Petterson's name
has been a matter of public record, and anyone can obtain a picture
of him for a 50-cent fee at the central passport office.
   Public records show Pettersson has a history of psychiatric
treatment, drug and alcohol abuse and a long criminal record,
including a conviction for manslaughter. Norwegian, Danish and
English papers published the name and photograph of Pettersson, and
foreign papers available in Stockholm were sold out at some news
stands.
   Many papers hailed the arrest and Friday's arraignment as a major
breakthrough in a case that has been a national frustration for
nearly three years. Government commissions accused police of
bungling in the crucial first days of the manhunt.
   The chief investigator has been replaced twice, and a private
investigation led to the resignation of Justice Minister Anna-Greta
Leijon in June. But prosecutors have put forward no motive, and the
murder weapon was not found.
   ``After nearly three years of uncertainty, the Palme murder is
now on the way to a solution,'' anchor man Jarl Alfredius said on
Friday's nightly news.
</TEXT>
