<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Cardinal 1stLd-Writhethru a0429 12-17 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Cardinal, 1st Ld - Writhethru, a0429,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Attacked During Mass; Assailant Beaten By Parishioners</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with man claiming to be possessed, ADDS
that Aquino pardoned or shortened sentences of 155 criminals.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CEBU CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic cardinal of Cebu
and two other priests were attacked and beaten during Mass today by
a man who told authorities he was possessed by the devil, police
said.
   Police and witnesses said Eduardo Espinosa barged into a church
in Talisay, seven miles south of this provincial city, rushed the
altar and struck Cardinal Ricardo Vidal in the face with his fist.
The cleric, his nose bloodied, fell back and hit his head on the
altar, authorities said.
   Police said two other priests, Rev. Achilles Dakay and Rev.
Hermingildo Montecillo, rushed to the cardinal's aid and also were
beaten.
   Dakay, a spokesman for the cardinal, said the attacker then raced
down the aisle, but parishoners intervened to beat and subdue him
until police arrived.
   Vidal, 57, is one of two cardinals in the Philippines. The other,
Cardinal Jaime L. Sin, is archbishop of Manila.
   Dakay said Vidal was able to complete the Mass, then drove to a
hospital where he was treated for facial and head contusions.
   Police officer Hannibal Larida said Espinosa, 33, was quoted as
telling police he was ``out of my mind'' when he attacked the
cardinal.
   ``It was an order from Satan,'' Larida quoted him as saying. The
police officer said Espinosa is a suspected drug addict.
   The Radio station DYHP said Espinosa had been in and out of
mental hospitals in Cebu since the 1970s.
   The station also quoted police as saying Espinosa may have
belonged to a satanic cult active in Cebu.
   In another development, President Corazon Aquino today pardoned
or shortened sentences for 155 convicts as part of her government's
program to ease extreme punishment for inmates.
   A presidential palace statement said the order included
conditional pardons for four convicts, parole for 13 and the
commutation of sentences for 138 others. The statement did not say
what crimes the prisoners committed.
</TEXT>
