<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BRF--ChappellConcedes     12-17 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Chappell Concedes,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veteran Congressman Gives Up Fight To Keep Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 20 years in Congress and more than
a month spent challenging his 791-vote loss to a Republican newcomer
in the Nov. 8 general election, Democratic U.S. Rep. William
Chappell has formally conceded.
   Craig James, whose campaign emphasized reports linking Chappell
to investigations of the Pentagon procurement scandal, defeated the
10-term incumbent by less than 1 percent of about 250,000 votes cast
in the northeast Florida district.
   ``I must acknowledge the Republican Party has won the seat in the
4th Congressional District of Florida, and I have decided against
pursuing a challenge any further,'' Chappell said Friday.
   Chappell, 66, sought to have the Florida Supreme Court throw out
nearly 11,000 votes from Flagler County because they arrived at the
state division of elections office one day after a seven-day state
deadline. That would have given him a 229-vote victory, but the
court turned back his request Nov. 30.
   Chappell has not been charged in any investigation of defense
contractors.
</TEXT>
