<1ST_LINE>u i PM-PLO-US 1stLd-Writethru a0463 12-17 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0463,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat: Goal Of Talks Peace Conference On Middle East</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with Arafat news conference. CHANGES byline. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat said today the Palestine
Liberation Organization's main priority in talks with the United
States is to push for an international peace conference on the
Middle East.
   Speaking with reporters after his arrival in Tunis a day after
the historic opening of an official U.S.-PLO dialogue, Arafat also
said he would do his best to prevent his followers from carrying out
any terrorist attacks.
   The PLO chairman described as a ``step in the right direction''
Friday's meeting between U.S. Ambassador Robert Pelletreau Jr. and a
four-man PLO delegation. Arafat said the PLO's prime objective in
the talks is ``to push forward for the international conference to
be held very soon.''
   Israel has rejected proposals for an international conference on
the Middle East, which would include the five permanent members of
the U.N. Security Council _ Britain, France, China, the United
States and the Soviet Union _ and the parties to the conflict.
   Asked if he could assure that no Palestinian terrorist attacks
would be staged, Arafat said it is difficult to control all
individuals or groups, but he added, ``We will do all our best to
stop all this.''
   Arafat also suggested, without providing any details, that he
played a role in the freeing Friday in Lebanon of Peter Winkler, a
Swiss official of the International Committee of the Red Cross who
had been kidnapped a month earlier. No group claimed responsibility
for his abduction.
   ``When I was in Geneva, the chief of the Red Cross asked me to
help release the Swiss employee, and he has been released,'' Arafat
said without elaborating.
   He condemned Israeli soldiers for killing at least four
Palestinians during clashes in the occupied lands on Friday.
   Arafat called it ``continuing state terrorism.'' He said, ``It is
a message from the Israeli military junta and the Israeli leaders
(who are) still refusing to accept peace, a just peaceful
settlement.''
   Arafat said the PLO and the United States had agreed to meet
again, but he did not say when. The chief PLO spokesman, Ahmed
Abdul-Rahman, said the next talks would take place after
President-elect George Bush takes office Jan. 20.
   Friday's meeting between delegations led by Pelletreau and Yasser
Abd-Rabbou, a member of the PLO executive committee, came two days
after Washington reversed a longstanding policy of refusing to deal
with the PLO.
   Washington said it did so because the PLO met conditions set for
the talks, including recognizing Isreal's right to exist and
renouncing terrorism.
   The historic session inspired hope in many quarters that advances
can be made in the Middle East peace process, which had stagnated
recently.
   ``We hope the application of this change in the policy of the
United States will be practiced through a real pressure on Israel in
order to change the policy of occupation, the policy of terrorism,
the policy of oppression against our Palestinian people,''
Abd-Rabbou said after the 90-minute session Friday.
   ``Our discussions were very practical and characterized, I would
say, by seriousness of purpose,'' Pelletreau said after his
90-minute session with a four-man PLO delegation. The U.S.
ambassador implied there would be other meetings but did not say
when.
   ``It is our hope that this dialogue, as it develops, will help
bring about direct negotiations that will lead to comprehensive
peace,'' said Pelletreau, who was accompanied to the talks by Edmund
Hull, political counselor at the U.S. Embassy in Tunis.
   The meeting took place at Dar Maghrebia, an official Tunisian
government guest residence in Carthage, a suburb just north of
Tunis. Neither side gave substantive details of the talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
