<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 1035EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Ireland-AIDS     12-17 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ireland-AIDS,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ireland's State-Run Lottery to Fund AIDS Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ireland's state-run lottery says it will
supply free syringes, needles and contraceptives to drug addicts to
help cut down their risk of contracting AIDS.
   The state-funded Eastern Health Board agreed to distribute the
items from two of its Dublin centers because of a high incidence of
needle sharing among drug addicts in the capital. The decisions were
made Friday.
   Three years ago, the Irish Parliament approved a bill to legalize
over-the-counter sales of contraceptives to anyone over 18 without a
doctor's prescription.
   It was the first time in the state's history that a government
had won a battle with the Roman Catholic Church, which opposes the
use of contraceptives. About 97 percent of the population is
Catholic.
   Lottery proceeds are used to finance projects in health, sports,
the arts and the Irish language.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
