<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 1035EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-JammingHalted 1stLd-Writethru a0482 12-17 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jamming Halted, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0482,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Stop Jamming of Radio Free Europe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with government confirming other jammers
also turned off, CORRECTING exec's name to Marsh, sted Morris. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia has stopped its
longtime jamming of the U.S.-owned Radio Free Europe broadcasting
network, the government announced today.
   Miroslav Pavel, a government spokesman, told The Associated Press
that jamming of Radio Free Europe was discontinued Friday and that
all other jammers were gradually switched off.
   The government also stopped jamming Deutsch Welle, a West German
station broadcasting in many languages, including Czech, according
to a source who spoke to The Associated Press on condition of
anonymity.
   The Czechoslovak plan to stop obstructing Western broadcasts was
announced earlier this week by Pavel and by diplomats in Vienna
attending the Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe.
   In Munich, Bill Marsh, Radio Free Europe executive vice
president, said Czechoslovakia has been jamming the network since
1968.
   Marsh said that with the Czech move, Bulgaria is the last Soviet
bloc country that continues to obstruct Radio Free Europe broadcast
signals.
</TEXT>
