<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Yakovlev     12-17 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Yakovlev,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Adviser Says Soviets Afraid of Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Communist Party Politburo member said in remarks
published Saturday that Soviets still are afraid of democracy and
openness despite more than three years of reform.
   ``We talk about political transformations, but how difficult it
is to part with the old power to which we are accustomed,''
Alexander N. Yakovlev said in the Ural Mountain city of Perm.
   ``We still cannot imagine that genuine people's power will be
simpler, more reliable and, of course, more responsible. Democracy,
glasnost, and differences of opinion still frighten us, as if every
one of us constantly lives in agreement with himself and always
thinks in comfortable cliches,'' Yakovlev said.
   ``Can you really call a person a person if he doesn't have his
own opinions?'' he said.
   His remarks to regional party officials were published by the
Communist Party newspaper Pravda.
   Yakovlev is regarded as a theoretician of Gorbachev's reforms and
the closest adviser to the Soviet president on the Politburo.
   He called for an end to ``wage-leveling,'' the practice of giving
people the same pay regardless of the quality of the work they do.
Gorbachev has encouraged the practice of paying more for better work
in an effort to get Soviets to work harder and produce better goods.
   Yakovlev said that practice could be encouraged through the
cooperative movement, which allows Soviets working privately to
provide goods and services scarce in the state-run economy without
adhering to the official price and wage structure.
   Without the concept of pay according to work, he said, ``the
construction of socialism is a utopia; without it society, a person
is alienated from property and power.''
   Yakovlev said the new government structure approved last month
will have to earn the respect of Soviet citizens.
   Last month, the Supreme Soviet parliament approved Gorbachev's
plan for a new Congress of People's Deputies that will include
members selected from the Communist Party, trade unions and other
organizations. The new congress in turn will choose a smaller, more
active Supreme Soviet.
   Gorbachev's plan also calls for a stronger presidency.
   Gorbachev, who became Communist Party chief in 1985, has said
economic restructuring is needed in Soviet society. He also has
espoused glasnost, or greater openness on selected issues.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
