<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Radio     12-17 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Radio,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan To Focus On Budget After Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan pledged today to work on
reforming the nation's budget process after leaving office, calling
the effort a ``vital campaign.''
   ``The budget system simply has no control and no internal
discipline. And that's the problem,'' Reagan said in his weekly
radio address, delivered from the Oval Office.
   With less than five weeks left in his presidency, Reagan used his
five-minute address to argue once again that the president needs
greater authority to limit spending in order to curtail the
country's deficit.
   In the 1988 fiscal year, which ended Sept. 30, a $155.1 billion
deficit was recorded. Under the Gramm-Rudman budget balancing law, a
$100 billion deficit target has been set for the 1990 fiscal year.
   Reagan blamed Congress for getting the nation into its red ink
dilemma, saying, ``Every dime of deficit spending has been mandated
by Congress.''
   Emphasizing that he believes the deficit can be solved without
raising taxes, Reagan also said such spending woes could be avoided
if a laundry list of changes in the budget process were enacted.
   The president has argued repeatedly during his White House tenure
for the proposals, such as the presidential authority to veto
individual items in appropriations bills, a constitutional amendment
requiring a balanced budget, and granting the president authority
not to spend money that Congress has appropriated, among others.
   ``Congress must reform its faulty budget process and we need a
balanced budget amendment to the Constitution so that the federal
government does not spend more than it takes in,'' Reagan said.
   ``After I leave office next month, I will campaign for these
reforms. So today, I'm asking you to join me in this vital campaign
for the future by making your voice heard. If we achieve these
reforms, the deficit will be ancient history in no time,'' Reagan
said.
   Reagan is required under the law to submit another budget on Jan.
9, and it is expected that he will include his budget reform
recommendations in that spending plan.
   President-elect George Bush has the option of scrapping Reagan's
entire budget if he wants and submitting his won proposal after he
takes office Jan. 20.
   Bush has declined to say whether he will submit his own plan, but
has said he wants to open negotiations with Congress over ways to
reduce the deficit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
