<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 1418EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece     12-17 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Papandreou Says He'll Resign if Parliament Rejects Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou, whose socialist
administration has been rocked by a financial scandal, said Saturday
the government will resign if Parliament does not approve his 1989
budget.
   The 69-year-old premier told a nationwide television audience
that he would consider a rejection of the nearly $28 billion budget
a no-confidence vote in his socialist government.
   ``If not approved, the government will resign with all the
consequences that would follow such an action'', he said. If the
government resigns because of failure to win a majority in the vote
scheduled for Sunday, general elections must be held within 45 days.
   Papandreou's speech came as rumors circulated through the Greek
capital that the government was about to collapse because of a
widening financial scandal.
   The scandal broke in October when opposition parties charged
senior government officials of involvement in illegal deals
allegedly set up by banker George Koskotas, who is accused of
influence peddling, embezzlement and fraud.
   The deals allegedly involved _ directly or indirectly _ the prime
minister and members of the governing Panhellenic Socialist
Movement, including Papandreou's son, George, who is Minister of
Education.
   Seven ministers have left the 59-member Cabinet as a result of
the $300 million banking and arms scandal. Koskotas, the former
chairman of the Bank of Crete, fled Greece Nov. 6 and has been
arrested in the United States.
   Koskotas, who ran a house-painting business in New York from 1974
to 1979, is also charged with attempting to defraud the U.S.
Internal Revenue Service. A hearing is scheduled in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan on Jan. 9.
   On Wednesday, Deputy Defense Minister Stathis Yiotas resigned,
saying: ``I refuse as a member of this government to be associated
with adventurers, swindlers and embezzlers of public money.''
   Yiotas charged the directors of the Greek Arms Industry of paying
commissions of millions of dollars for unfulfilled contracts to arms
dealers hiding behind dummy companies.
   He also resigned his seat in Parliament and left the governing
party's central committee.
   The scandal widened when a banking commissioner investigating the
Bank of Crete said public service organizations had more than $133
million on deposit with the bank.
   
   Greek newspapers and opposition political parties accused
officials working for the post office, telephone company and other
public services of receiving interest rates above the legal limit
from the bank and pocketing the difference.
   
   In his speech, Papandreou charged ``domestic and foreign
circles'' of ``undermining and orchestrating'' the overthrow of his
socialist administration, basing ``their hopes in God that I would
not return from London.'' He did not elaborate. Papandreou underwent
bypass cardiac surgery there on September 30.
   Political observers said Papandreou's speech appeared to be a
warning to his deputies to adhere to the party line or _ if they
failed to approve the government's budget _ be considered defectors.
According to parliamentary procedure, lawmakers cast ballots by
voice vote and therefore are hesitant to oppose party policy.
   His party controls 157 seats in the 300-member single-chamber
Parliament, the conservative New Democracy party has 112 seats, the
Communist Party 12, and other parties, 19.
   Debate on the budget began Thursday and a vote is scheduled for
Sunday.
   New Democracy, led by Constantine Mitsotakis, has called on the
government to resign and call elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
