<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: k.d. lang in 3rd item is cq.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Hawaii's richest snowbirds has received
state permission to bring two pet camels to winter in paradise.
   Reclusive tobacco heiress Doris Duke and her newly adopted
daughter want to ship Princess and Baby, 1-year-old female Bactrian
camels, from Ms. Duke's New Jersey estate to her 4.9-acre beachfront
estate in the posh Honolulu neighborhood of Black Point, attorney
Ronald Y.K. Leong told the state Board of Agriculture on Friday.
   Ms. Duke and adopted daughter Charlene Gail ``Chandi'' Heffner,
35, spend late November to early April in the islands, Leong said.
   The panel unanimously approved the request to allow Princess and
Baby to join Ms. Duke and Heffner. Friday's hearing was necessary to
comply with Hawaii's stringent laws governing the importation of
animals.
   Leong said Princess and Baby live inside Ms. Duke's New Jersey
mansion. He did not know whether the animals would live inside or
outside of Ms. Duke's Honolulu home.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Stewart, Frank Sinatra and Amy Irving
donated some Christmas cheer to the Make a Wish Foundation, which
grants wishes for children with life-threatening illnesses.
   A silent auction was held Friday at a downtown office building,
the California Plaza. The celebrities donated Christmas stockings
that they decorated themselves, said Lynn Feldman, a publicist for
the affair.
   ``It was surprising,'' she said. ``People bid the highest amounts
of money for some of the older celebrities.''
   Jimmy Stewart's stocking got the biggest draw, at $200. A
stocking donated by ``Old Blue Eyes'' got a $155 bid. A stocking
from Tom Cruise drew a $100 bid and Amy Irving's went for $70.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A section of street became ``Kitty Wells
Boulevard'' Saturday in honor of the singer known as the ``queen of
country music.''
   The portion of Old Hickory Boulevard runs in front of a music
museum operated since 1983 by Miss Wells and her husband, country
singer Johnny Wright.
   Miss Wells, who was inducted into the Country Music Hall of Fame
in 1976, is best known for her hit song ``It Wasn't God Who Made
Honky-Tonk Angels.''
   Earlier this year, she joined singers k.d. lang, Loretta Lynn and
Brenda Lee on the record ``Honky-Tonk Angels Medley.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DOWNEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Farrell, Sally Kellerman and other
celebrities chatted with patients and distributed gifts Saturday at
the annual Academy of Television Arts & Sciences party at Rancho Los
Amigos Medical Center.
   Stars boarded buses at the Screen Actors Guild offices in
Hollywood and traveled to the rehabilitation center in southeast Los
Angeles County for daylong festivities including celebrity-patient
wheelchair races.
   ``The patients always win, by the way,'' said academy official
Jim Malinda, directing teams of stars through the wards from a
command post. ``The patients are a little bit better in the
wheelchairs.''
   The academy's 19th annual visit celebrated the center's 100th
birthday.
   The visit is officially called the Allen Ludden Rancho Los Amigos
Medical Center Holiday Party, after the late host of the
``Password'' TV show. Several other stars also planned to attend
throughout the day.
   The academy buys gifts such as TV sets and videocassette
recorders for all of the 450 patients, said event spokesman Murray
Weissman.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The writer-director of ``Platoon,'' ``Wall
Street'' and ``Talk Radio,'' known for his angry film characters,
says parenthood and marriage counseling have mellowed him.
   ``You probe your feelings and your relationship to your mom, your
relationship to women, whether you're a misogynist or not,'' Oliver
Stone said, adding, ``The issue came up: `Why in your films do you
treat (women negatively)?''
   ``And I think there's some truth to it. I think there's some
anger and hostilities that I had toward my mother that are still
being worked out,'' Stone said in the January issue of Vanity Fair.
``There was an ugly divorce and it came at age 14, a crucial age.''
   ``And having a child has, brings things out, these repressed
things,'' he added. ``I'm bringing out the woman in me more and more
in my work. I think I made big strides in `Talk Radio.'''
   In an angrier period of his life, Stone said, he returned from
Vietnam combat duty to live in a seamy, New York City tenement
painted blood-red from floor to ceiling.
   ``I believed in (Jim) Morrison's incantation. `Break on through.
Kill the pigs. Destroy. Loot,''' he said.
   ``If the right people had said the right things to me, I might
have gone after (President Richard) Nixon,'' Stone said, confirming
that he meant killing the former president. ``Oh, yeah, yeah. If I'd
felt the flood was with me. There was a moment there. It could have
happened.''
   The homicidal component of his rage has been sublimated in his
screenplays and _ now that he's a husband and father _ ``the
suicidal impulses are gone,'' Stone said casually.
</TEXT>
