<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MemorialSong     12-17 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Memorial Song,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Popular Song Recorded by Officer Shortly Before His Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A song in memory of fallen police
officers, written and recorded by a policeman who died two days
later in an accident, has become the most popular song at the radio
station where it debuted.
   The calls to WQIK-FM haven't stopped since the song ``When Daddy
Comes Home'' was first played Friday.
   ``We have just been swamped on the phones,'' program director
Jack Evans said. ``It's been the most requested song of the day.''
   Officer Ray Shinholser, 30, died Wednesday from injuries suffered
when he was thrown from his motorcycle Tuesday night on his way to
work. His funeral was Saturday.
   After Shinholser's death, his 4-year-old son Michael's voice was
added to the song, reciting the plaintive refrain, ``I miss you,
Daddy. I miss you.''
   ``That's it. That's the part that really gets to people,'' said
Officer Jimmy Guthrie, secretary of the Fraternal Order of Police.
   Michael, Shinholser's widow, Debbie, the officer's manager and
two fellow officers brought the first copy of the song's master tape
to WQIK Thursday night.
   The song was inspired by the death of Officer Gary Bevel, who was
fatally shot in May 1983. But the lyrics foreshadow the songwriter's
own death, saying in part, ``Momma, when's Daddy coming home to hug
his little man?''
   WQIK news director Tim Maguire called the offices of syndicated
radio commentator Paul Harvey in Chicago this week to relay the
story; Harvey opened his Thursday broadcast with Shinholser's story.
   Guthrie said his office has received hundreds of calls from radio
listeners wanting to buy the tape.
   Shinholser originally intended all proceeds to go toward the
construction fund for a police memorial in Washington, Guthrie said.
Now, part of the profits will be placed in a college fund for
Shinholser's two children.
   The police union is producing tapes of the song.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   (EDITOR'S NOTE: The tapes may be ordered by calling 904-354-0952.)
</TEXT>
