<1ST_LINE>u w AM-PLORdp     12-17 1143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO Rdp,3rd Ld-Writethru,a0548,1,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top State Department Official Warns PLO Terrorism Would End US
Dialogue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores first reference to Shultz in graf 20 and dropped word
``was'' in graf 26</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States informed the Palestine
Liberation Organization that if it engages in terrorism the newly
opened U.S. talks would be discontinued, a top State Department
official said Saturday.
   ``There is no way this dialogue can be sustained if terrorism is
persistent and traceable to known elements of the PLO,'' Assistant
Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy said.
   Murphy, in an interview with The Associated Press, said Robert H.
Pelletreau Jr., the U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, made the point
strenuously to a PLO delegation in their talk Friday in Carthage, an
ancient city on the outskirts of Tunis.
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat, at a brief news conference at PLO
headquarters in Tunis, Tunisia, said Saturday that the PLO would
``do all our best to stop'' terrorism but said he could not
guarantee that ``one person here or individual there'' might not
ignore his wishes.
   Arafat said the PLO's main priority in the talks is to push for
an early convening of an international peace conference on the
Middle East. The United States has said any resolution of the Middle
East crisis would have to come from direct negotiations between
Israel and its neighbors, while Israel has refused to include the
PLO in any talks.
   Arafat described Friday's meeting as a ``step in the right
direction'' toward a ``just and comprehensive settlement.''
   At the same news conference, PLO spokesman Ahmed Abdul-Rahman
charged that Israel was trying to undermine the U.S.-PLO contacts by
using deadly force against Palestinians.
   One potential sticking point in the talks was apparent:
Abdul-Rahman said a settlement must include establishment of an
independent Palestinian state while the United States has said its
decision to open a dialogue with the PLO did not affect U.S.
opposition to such a state.
   Friday's session was the first authorized U.S. meeting with the
PLO in at least 13 years. No further meetings have been scheduled as
yet, said Murphy, who said major developments in the final five
weeks of the Reagan administration are unlikely. Abdul-Rahman said
he did not expect a second meeting until after President-elect Bush
takes office next month.
   Murphy said terrorism was the ``lead item'' on the U.S. agenda
and took up half of the 75-minute meeting with a four-man PLO
delegation.
   While the PLO did not make a specific promise in response, Murphy
said, ``there was the general comment from their side that this
dialogue is too important to have it messed up.''
   The PLO delegation implied Arafat would make a special effort to
restrict the activities of more radical elements, said Murphy, the
State Department's senior Middle East specialist.
   Some Palestinian leaders have denounced Arafat's statements on
Israel. Official newspapers in Syria also opposed the U.S.-PLO
meeting, saying ``real peace should be taken by force,'' while
President Ali Khamenei of Iran said at a prayer meeting Friday in
Tehran that ``the way to fight Zionism is by force and power.''
   In Jerusalem, Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said he was
shocked by the U.S. decision and announced he was preparing a new
peace initiative.
   ``Of course it's painful to receive such a blow, especially from
friends,'' Shamir said on Israel radio. ``But let's not exaggerate,
we have had differences of opinion with our friends.'' Shamir has
offered to hold direct peace talks with Jordan while excluding the
PLO.
   Former Secretary of State Henry A. Kissinger had promised Israel
in 1975 the United States would shun the PLO if it did not accept
the legitimacy of the Jewish state. The promise helped induce Israel
to relinquish land in the Sinai desert to Egypt.
   Murphy said the PLO delegation made the point to Pelletreau that
``not everybody is under PLO control'' and can be deterred from
terrorism. ``That obviously is not going to be a sustainable
position should there be a rash of incidents which we would term
terrorism,'' Murphy said.
   Arafat on Wednesday renounced terrorism ``in all forms.'' The
statement was one of three conditions set by the United States for
opening talks with the PLO.
   The two other conditions were explicit acceptance of Israel's
right to exist and approval of 1967 and 1973 resolutions of the U.N.
Security Council affirming all Middle Eastern countries should be
able to live in peace within secure boundaries.
   A little more than two weeks earlier, Secretary of State George
P. Shultz had condemned the PLO as a terrorist organization, called
Arafat an ``accessory'' to terrorism and denied the PLO chairman
permission to speak before the United Nations in New York.
   As a result, the U.N. General Assembly shifted its debate on the
Arab-Israeli dispute to Geneva.
   Murphy said Shultz's decision authorizing ``substantive
dialogue'' with the PLO had not changed Shultz's view of the PLO or
his opposition to establishment of a Palestinian state.
   In fact, the U.S. official said, ``nothing that happened
Wednesday has changed our position or approach to the peace
process.''
   These include the view that an independent Palestinian state on
the West Bank and Gaza, which are now held by Israel, would not be
viable, and that the PLO should not have a separate seat in any
Mideast peace talks.
   ``We haven't pulled back from any of the Shultz initiative,''
Murphy said.
   He referred to the plan for Arab-Israeli negotiations Shultz took
to the Middle East earlier this year. It was not accepted by Israel
and Jordan, while Palestinian Arabs invited to meet with him in
Jerusalem did not show up.
   Key features of the U.S. proposal included a joint delegation of
Jordanians and Palestinians to negotiate with Israel and having
Israel give up some _ but not all _ of the land it won in the 1967
Middle East war.
   Murphy said Pelletreau's meeting with PLO officials ``didn't
answer any of the tough problems'' but with a U.S. dialogue
established it will be easier for the United States and the PLO to
understand each other's positions.
   In the past, Murphy said, Saudi Arabia and Egypt had informed the
PLO of where the United States stood. ``Cutting out the third party
in a conversation should make it clearer,'' he said.
   The decision to open the dialogue, meanwhile, won praise from
West Virginia Sen. Robert C. Byrd, the outgoing Senate majority
leader.
   Byrd, in the Democratic Party's weekly radio address, said the
PLO's meeting of the U.S. conditions was ``long overdue'' and said
progress would depend on Arafat's success in controlling ``those
factions within the PLO who believe that terrorism is a legitimate
recourse.''
   Byrd called on Israel to support the dialogue as ``an opportunity
to be seized, an opportunity to develop a new national consensus
regarding negotiations with the PLO.''
</TEXT>
