<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-MysteryCrash     12-17 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Mystery Crash,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search Resumes for Crashed Lear Jet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of two Americans were
recovered Saturday from the remains of a Lear jet that inexplicably
bypassed its Texas destination and crashed in the mountains of
northeastern Mexico, authorities said.
   Ernesto Marquez Rivera, Coahuila state district attorney in
Monclova, said by telephone that the bodies of a man and a woman
were recovered early Saturday from the wreckage.
   He identified the bodies by their driver's licenses as Susan
Reynolds, 27, and Larry Morris, 39, both of Dallas.
   The bodies were taken to a funeral home in the small town
Cuatrocienegas, about 40 miles north of the crash site, Marquez
said. He said they would be taken later to Monclova, about 50 miles
east of there, for autopsy.
   Roger Walsh, U.S. consular section chief in this capital city,
said a consular representative had been sent to Monclova to identify
the bodies.
   Marquez said the plane was found intact but badly damaged in the
brush of the mountainside. ``There wasn't a fire,'' he said. ``The
bodies have been beaten up but not burned.''
   Walsh said he could give no further details about the plane's
occupants until their families are notified. He said the consulate
would help the families return the bodies to the United States.
   Marquez said federal authorities would investigate the crash to
determine a cause.
   The jet, with two people aboard, left Memphis, Tenn., shortly
after 5 a.m. Friday with a flight plan for Addison Airport, a suburb
north of Dallas, according to the Federal Aviation Administration in
Dallas and the U.S. Embassy in Mexico City.
   It crashed between 7 and 8 a.m. in the mountains about 100 miles
northwest of this northern capital city, the embassy said.
   Why the Dallas-based jet overflew its destination remained a
mystery Saturday.
   An F-16 and another plane tried to contact the jet's pilot after
it climbed to more than 40,000 feet, but the pilot did not respond,
the FAA said.
   Roger Crownrich, the craft's owner, said the plane was ``bound to
be on autopilot.''
   He identified the plane's co-pilot as 25-year-old Susan Reynolds,
a graduate electrical engineer and a former NASA employee.
   Crownrich, the owner of Crownrich Construction Management Inc. in
Dallas, said the plane was on a charter run at the time of the
crash. He said the regular pilot was not aboard the plane and he
didn't know who was flying with Ms. Reynolds.
   He said Ms. Reynolds and a pilot flew to Memphis regularly to
pick up Federal Express packages for delivery.
</TEXT>
