<DOCNO> AP881217-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 1627EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Iran     12-17 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Iran,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Ready To Help Iran Rebuild After War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leader Zhao Ziyang told Iran's
foreign minister Saturday that China is ready to help Iran
reconstruct its economy after the eight-year Persian Gulf war, an
official report said.
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati told Zhao that Iran
``welcomes very much'' China's participation, the Xinhua News Agency
said.
   Velayati also briefed Zhao on the stalled Iran-Iraq peace talks
in Geneva, Xinhua said.
   The Iranian official, who returned home Saturday after a
three-day visit, told reporters that he also discussed the same
issues with Premier Li Peng and Chinese Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen. He described the talks as fruitful, but did not elaborate.
   Velayati said China expressed interest in helping build
factories, dams, railroads and agricultural projects in Iran. But he
said no details had been worked out, and Iran had not asked China
for loans.
   The Iranian official also denied a recent report by diplomatic
sources in the Middle East that China delivered 50 J-6 and F-7
fighter jets to Iran before a cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war took
effect Aug. 20.
   He reiterated Iran's claim that it captured its Chinese-made
weapons in battle from Iraq.
   China also has denied selling weapons to Iran, but U.S. and other
third-country sources say China has been one of Iran's main arms
suppliers.
   Mednews, a Paris-based newsletter specializing in Middle East
defense issues, said the jets were part of a 1985 agreement that
also called for China to supply air-to-air missiles and
air-to-ground rockets.
   Iran has positioned Chinese-made Silkworm missiles at the
entrance to the Persian Gulf and a U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tanker was
attacked last year by such a missile. The United States responded by
briefly suspending its liberalization of technology sales to China.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
