<DOCNO> AP881217-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 1636EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain     12-17 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain Rules Out Early Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Saturday ruled out calling
early elections in response to a one-day general strike against
economic policies that shut down nearly all business and labor
activity.
   Government spokeswoman Rosa Conde told reporters no resignations
of any ministers were planned due to Wednesday's strike by the two
major leftist unions. She reiterated the Socialist administration's
willingness to open wide-ranging talks with the two major leftist
unions that organized it and top business leaders.
   But the Socialist-led General Workers Union and the
Communist-dominated Workers Commissions again rejected Socialist
Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez's offer to take part in talks with
the government and the head of the nation's key business
organization.
   The Socialists hold a comfortable majority in Parliament and do
not have to call elections until June 1990.
   The general strike was the first in 54 years. The unions want
unemployment insurance coverage broadened to include up to 48
percent of Spain's 2.7 million jobless and the smallest retirement
pensions increased to the legal monthly minimum wage of $394.
   Ms. Conde said a government representative, perhaps Gonzalez,
would explain the administration's view of the strike and the
demands of the unions before parliament Wednesday.
   Gonzalez issued a statement a day after the strike acknowledging
it as a ``political success'' and a ``tough political blow to the
government.'' He repeated his offer to discuss demands with unions
and the head of the top business organization.
   On Friday, leaders of the socialist-led General Workers Union and
the communist-dominated Workers Commissions appeared at a large,
peaceful demonstration in central Madrid and rejected the meeting
offered by Gonzalez if he insists the head of the nation's key
business organization attend.
   At least 40,000 people attended the rally.
   Despite an economic growth rate of 5 percent annually that puts
it at the top of Western European economies, 18.7 percent of the
people are unemployed, Europe's highest rate. Union leaders and
members have argued the time has come to share more of the spoils of
economic boom with workers and the poor.
</TEXT>
