<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviets-Berlin     12-17 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Berlin,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Plane Makes First Flight To West Berlin To Pick Up Quake
Relief</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Aeroflot plane landed Saturday in West Berlin to
pick up supplies for quake-devastated Armenia, the first time in
memory Western officials allowed a Soviet plane to touch down in the
western sector of the divided city.
   Aeroflot announced that the four-engined IL-76 airplane, which
landed at Tegel Airport, was to pick up blankets, medical goods and
warm clothing collected by the German Red Cross and other groups.
   Aeroflot did not announce when the plane was scheduled to leave
Berlin.
   The U.S. Air Force also has volunteered its service in the relief
effort, flying goods into Soviet Armenia for victims of the Dec. 7
quake that officials say killed an estimated 55,000 people, injured
thousands and left a half million homeless.
   Meanwhile, West German contributions to the massive international
aid effort continue to grow. According to the West Berlin newspaper
Tagespiegel, the giant West German pharmaceutical company Schering
is donating $360,000 of medical goods to the relief cause.
   Berlin, the former German capital which lies inside communist
East Germany, has been divided into a communist eastern sector and
capitalist western sectors since the end of World War II. From June
1948 to September 1949, Soviet forces imposed a land blockade on the
western sectors, forcing the Allies to fly tons of supplies to
residents from the West in an operation known as the Berlin Airlift.
In 1950 the U.S., British and French western sectors were unified
into a West German state.
</TEXT>
