<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan     12-17 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels, Soviets Discuss Exchanging Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet delegation on Saturday opened
a new round of talks on prisoner exchanges with Afghan guerrillas,
who said the Soviets refused to move the discussions beyond that
issue.
   Radio Kabul reported, in an apparent reference to guerrillas,
that ``criminal extremists'' blasted Mehthar Lam, the capital of the
northeastern province of Laghman, with 1,500 rockets over the last
three days. The radio said 15 people were killed and 24 injured.
   The radio report, monitored in Islamabad, said Afghan government
troops repulsed the guerrillas who were trying to overtake the city
about 60 miles northeast of the Afghan capital Kabul.
   The talks in Islamabad, Pakistan's capital, centered on return of
four Soviet soldiers held by guerrillas in Afghanistan's northern
Baghlan province, said Abdul Rahim, one of two guerrilla delegates
to the talks.
   He said the Soviets, who back the Marxist Afghan government with
thousands of troops, refused to move the talks beyond prisoner
exchange. He said attempts to steer talks toward what guerrillas
call a Soviet escalation of combat failed.
   ``We showed our concern that we thought they were not serious''
about peace, he said.
   The guerrillas say about 5,000 Soviet soldiers have returned to
the southern city of Kandahar in recent days. Afghanistan's
second-largest city, Kandahar has been under guerrilla seige for
several months.
   There has been no independent confirmation of a renewed Soviet
presence there.
   The Soviet Union, which sent its forces to Afghanistan in
December 1979, began withdrawing its troops in May under an
agreement brokered by the United Nations. Half of more than 100,000
Soviet troops left the country by Aug. 15 and remainder are to leave
by Feb. 15.
   Rahim said the four-member Soviet delegation wanted proof of the
identity of the four Red Army prisoners.
   The rebel representative said it is impossible to show the
Soviets the four prisoners because of the ``war situation.''
   He accused the Soviets of stalling the exchange. He said the
guerrillas, known as mujahedeen, or islamic warriors, are ready to
hand the four prisoners over for 100 guerrillas.
   ``They are delaying _ not us,'' said Rahim.
   The one-hour meeting in Islamabad on Saturday ended without any
agreement, he said.
   The Soviet Embassy declined to make any immediate comment.
   An earlier round of Soviet-rebel talks in Saudi Arabia in
November ended without reports of significant progress. Another
round of talks is expected to be held in Islamabad later this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
