<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GangControl     12-17 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Control,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Cuts Off Funds For Gang-Control Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor W. Wilson Goode has cut off funds to a
gang-control organization once considered a model program for
reducing street tension, forcing a halt to its programs.
   Goode said Friday that the Crisis Intervention Network's
financial problems, including a $203,000 debt to the Internal
Revenue Service, were insurmountable.
   ``We will not use city funds to pay off an old debt,'' he said.
   The mayor said he hoped the private, non-profit agency's program
and employees could be absorbed by another agency so that its work
could continue, but he said no alternatives have been explored.
   The group's executive director, Bennie J. Swans, said 38 of the
48 employees were laid off Friday and its programs were shut down.
He said he and the other nine employees would stay until Jan. 5,
when city funding ends, to tie up loose ends and try to find another
source of funds.
   ``Everyone agrees we've performed a valuable service,'' Swans
said. ``I think that the services are sorely needed in the community
and I think people are going to suffer because of it.''
   The decision to close the agency came after months of uncertainty
over its future, sparked by complaints of financial mismanagement.
   The Crisis Intervention Network was founded in 1975 as an arm of
city government.
   Its approach to gang warfare _ using street-savvy workers, many
of them former gang members, to mediate disputes and reduce
community tension _ won praise and became a model for programs
around the country.
   The network became a private, non-profit agency in 1979, but the
city has remained its principal source of funds, with city contracts
paying $1.5 million or more in each of the past three years.
   But three months ago, a group of current and former employees
wrote to elected officials and news media accusing Swans of spending
abuses and mismanagement.
   Swans called the allegations groundless, but acknowledged
bookkeeping problems, including a failure to send to the IRS about
$80,000 withheld from employee paychecks.
   The IRS filed a $203,000 lien against the network Dec. 9, said
David Kairys, co-chairman of the agency's board. He said the board
had not decided ``whether it's over, whether to reorganize,
bankruptcy. ... We have choices.''
   ``I think the city has gotten used to CIN stepping in when things
get hot,'' Kairys said. ``We are the envy of cities around the
country. It just seems unnecessary and detrimental for the city to
cut off the funding.''
</TEXT>
