<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-17 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow in the East; Nice in the West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   New England was bracing for a winter storm Saturday that was to
bring up to 8 inches of snow, while temperatures were in the 60s and
70s in the South and the desert Southwest.
   A low pressure system off the mid-Atlantic coast was moving
northeast Saturday, prompting the National Weather Service to post
winter storm warnings for portions of Massachusetts and Maine, and
snow advisories for the rest of southern New England and portions of
New York.
   A gale warning was posted for the coasts of New Hampshire and
Maine.
   Snow showers brought light snow to the lower Great Lakes region,
and snow advisories were posted in the northern mountains of North
Carolina, Maryland and West Virginia.
   A heavy snow warning was posted for Ohio, where up to 15 inches
of snow were expected by Sunday morning. A snow advisory remained in
effect for the southern Sierra Nevada range of central California
   Snowfall totals for a six-hour period ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 2 inches at Marquette, Mich., and 1 inch at Charleston,
W.Va.
   Temperatures were in the 50s and 60s across Florida and the
central Gulf Coast region and in the 60s and 70s in the southwestern
deserts.
   But temperatures were below freezing from eastern Montana through
the Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes region, with readings in the
teens from North Dakota to upper Michigan.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 2
degrees in the Maine cities of Caribou and Limestone, to 77 degrees
at Chandler, Ariz. The nation's low Saturday morning was 18 degrees
below zero at Houlton, Maine.
   The forecast for Sunday called for snow from the Great Lakes
region and the upper Ohio Valley to New England, and rain across
southern and central California into western Arizona.
   Mostly cloudy skies were forecast from the upper Mississippi
valley to the Tennessee Valley. Sunny skies will prevail across the
rest of the nation.
   Temperatures will remain below freezing all day from North Dakota
through the Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes region to the middle and
northern Atlantic coast, with highs in the teens from Michigan
through New York and New England.
   Readings above 50 degrees were expected in much of California
through the southern Plains, the lower Mississippi Valley into
Florida, with readings in the 30s and 40s in most of the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
