<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hatcher-Jacobs     12-17 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hatcher-Jacobs,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Indian Defendant Flees to Reservation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBIN P. TEATER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second defendant charged in the takeover
of a North Carolina newspaper has fled to a New York Indian
reservation, saying he is in fear for his life, his attorney said
Saturday.
   ``I view him as I would anyone fleeing a Third World
dictatorship,'' Ron Kuby, one of Eddie Hatcher's attorneys, said in
a telephone interview from his New York office. ``He has no
intention of returning to Robeson County unless or until democracy
is restored there.''
   He said Hatcher had telephoned him to say he was in New York but
would not specify where.
   However, in a phone call Saturday to The Associated Press,
Hatcher said he was with co-defendant Timothy Jacobs on the Onondaga
Indian Reservation near Syracuse, N.Y.
   ``I have left North Carolina,'' he said. ``I have taken sanctuary
in New York and I intend to stay here. I cannot be forced back.
There is no jurisdiction where I am. The United States has no
jurisdiction, and the state of New York does not.''
   Hatcher, 31, and Jacobs, 20, were indicted Dec. 6 by a Robeson
County, N.C., grand jury on state kidnapping charges, less than two
months after they were acquitted of federal hostage-taking charges
in the Feb. 1 takeover of The Robesonian newspaper in Lumberton. A
trial date has not been set.
   Hatcher and Jacobs contend taking over the newspaper was the only
way they could draw attention to what they call public corruption in
Robeson County.
   Hatcher was free on $25,000 bond posted by the National Council
of Churches, with the stipulation that he stay in Robeson County and
appear for his court dates.
   ``This would appear to violate that,'' Kuby said. ``It's
unfortunate, but I understand why he did it.''
   Hatcher said he had written a letter to National Council of
Churches officials.
   ``I'm sure they will understandand it will be worked out in the
end,'' he said. ``They realize the situation we're in and they're
sympathetic to our cause.''
   No one answered the telephone Saturday afternoon at the church
group's headquarters in New York City.
   The Onondaga County Sheriff's Department said Saturday that it
had no jurisdiction over the reservation and could not go onto the
property to look for Hatcher.
   Robeson County officials said Saturday they had no information on
Hatcher's whereabouts.
   ``We did not have him under surveillance,'' said Jimmy Maynor,
chief of detectives for the sheriff's department. ``If he has fled
to avoid prosecution, then necessary steps will be taken if he fails
to appear in court.''
   Onondaga Indian Chief Leon Shenandoah, reached at his home
Saturday, said he did not know where Hatcher was and refused further
comment.
   Jacobs fled to the New York reservation when the state charges
were filed and was arrested Tuesday after a car chase with state
police near Oneida, N.Y. He is scheduled to appear in Madison
County, N.Y., court Jan. 12 on charges stemming from the chase.
   He was released Friday under $25,000 bond, also posted by the
Council of Churches, after Onondaga Indian leaders gave a sworn
statement that they would not harbor him if New York Gov. Mario
Cuomo orders his extradition to North Carolina.
   Gov. Jim Martin has said he'll push for Jacobs' extradition.
   Kuby said Hatcher said he has received recent death threats.
   ``I will not return to North Carolina until we have a just system
of government in North Carolina and that means the resignation of
Governor Jim Martin and his blood-thirsty vultures,'' Hatcher said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
