<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionProtests 1stLd-Writethru a0579 12-17 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Protests, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0579,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More than 200 Arrested in Anti-abortion Protests</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with demonstrations in Georgia,
Indiana, picking up 3rd graf, `In Harrisburg...'. ADDS 6 grafs on
end with detail. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A patient was knocked to the ground Saturday during an
anti-abortion protest at a clinic in Pennsylvania, one of six states
where demonstrations were held. More than 300 people were arrested.
   Police arrested 79 protesters in Harrisburg, Pa.; 58 in Baton
Rouge, La.; 101 in Concord, Calif.; 40 in Chamblee, Ga.; 13 in
Indianapolis; and 20 in Dallas.
   In Harrisburg, about 175 demonstrators gathered outside the
Hillcrest Women's Clinic, authorities said. The majority of the
protesters were men, said Peggy Ross, director of educational
programs for the clinic.
   One man knocked a patient and an escort to the ground, but no one
was hurt, she said.
   The demonstration did not disrupt operations at the clinic, she
said, adding, ``None of our patients called in to cancel.''
   Chris Kahlenborn, one of the demonstrators, said the group was
``under the principles of Operation Rescue,'' referring to a
Binghamton, N.Y.-based group that orchestrated protests this year at
the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta and in dozens of other
cities around the nation, resulting in more than 9,000 arrests.
   Harrisburg Police Cpl. Frank Fauasuli said all the people
arrested were released a short time later. They will be subject to a
fine of up to $300.
   In Baton Rouge, La., about 500 people gathered outside the Delta
Women's Clinic, and arrests numbered at least 58, authorities said.
   Protesters took as long as an hour to crawl on their knees from
clinic entrances to police buses.
   ``I was hoping it would slow them down and keep the clinic closed
this morning,'' said one demonstrator, Louisiana State University
graduate student Thomas Palfrey. ``I'm here to protest the killing
of unborn babies and lend support to the women who realize the pain
and guilt after abortion.''
   Patients began arriving at the clinic about 6 a.m., about an hour
before the protesters, and the clinic closed about 9:30 a.m. when
all the patients had been seen.
   ``We did procedures this morning and the patients are ready to
leave,'' said spokeswoman Esther McGuire. ``Their goal was not
achieved. Abortions have been performed.''
   Baton Rouge Police Chief Wayne Rogillio said those arrested would
be charged under a city ordinance for failure to leave a premises _
a misdemeanor carrying a maximum penalty of a $500 fine and 30 days
in jail.
   Saturday's demonstration followed similar protests on Friday at
another Baton Rouge clinic, where 108 of about 250 protesters were
arrested.
   In Concord, Calif., 101 people were arrested Saturday outside a
Planned Parenthood clinic at an Operation Rescue-organized
demonstration. Police Lt. Dick Burns said protesters did not resist
arrest.
   About 35 to 50 counterprotesters also were at the clinic, Burns
said.
   Another Operation Rescue protest was held in Dallas, where 200
people rallied outside a clinic.
   One of the 20 protesters arrested on criminal trespass complaints
was Joan Elizabeth Andrews, who served 2{ years of a five-year
prison term in Florida after being arrested outside a Pensacola
clinic in March 1986.
   Protesters carried placards with photographs of dead fetuses and
slogans such as: ``Abortion is murder'' and ``I didn't know murder
was legalized.''
   In Chamblee, Ga., an Atlanta suburb, 40 people were taken into
custody after they formed a barricade at the doors of the Northside
Women's Clinic, police said. In all, the protesters there Saturday
numbered about 250.
   Chamblee Police Chief Reed Miller said officers carried the 40
protesters on stretchers to a paddy wagon and a bus. The protesters
were charged with interfering with a business. The misdemeanor
charge is punishable by up to $500 in fines or 30 days in jail.
   ``They were peaceful,'' Miller said. ``They blocked doors until
we had them removed.''
   In Indianapolis, the 13 protesters arrested outside Affiliated
Women's Services were charged with criminal trespassing, which
carries a maximum penalty of a year's in jail and a $5,000 fine.
   ``We had to physically carry them off, but they were very
cooperative,'' said Deputy Chief Mike Hoak of the Marion County
Sheriff's Department.
   Dozens of demonstrators affiliated with the Operation Rescue
gathered in the morning outside the clinic in an industrial park
near Indianapolis International Airport.
</TEXT>
