<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DoubleShooting     12-17 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Double Shooting,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Kills Ailing, Retarded Daughter, Then Himself, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALSIP, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly man despondent over his retarded
36-year-old daughter's illness shot her to death and turned the gun
on himself, neighbors and family members said.
   Police were still investigating the double shooting, but Police
Chief Warner T. Huston said it's ``a pretty clear case of a
homicide-suicide.''
   Edward DeYoung, a 73-year-old retired truck driver, and his
daughter, Annie, were found Thursday in the woman's bedroom. Each
had bullet wound in the head.
   Miss DeYoung lay in bed in her pajamas, a stuffed dog tucked in
her arms.
   ``It's sad that it happened, but I can understand why he did what
he did,'' said neighbor Peggy Barron, 39. ``He hated to see her
suffer. He loved her.''
   Miss DeYoung was discharged Wednesday from Christ Hospital in Oak
Lawn, where she was admitted Oct. 31 for treatment of a large tumor,
apparently non-cancerous, on her neck. Her father spent most of his
time with her at the hospital, as she went through surgery and tests.
   DeYoung took his daughter home the day before their bodies were
found, according to his grandson, James DeYoung Jr., 27. She was
depressed and not eating, he said.
   ``We had no hint something like this would happen,'' the grandson
said. ``Maybe Ed thought she was going to suffer.''
   DeYoung left a suicide note saying ``he was sorry, that God told
him this is what he had to do,'' said Huston.
   Dr. Mary Jumbelic of the Cook County medical examiner's office
said tests on the woman's body showed no signs of cancer, but that
she did have ``endocrine abnormalities.'' She said further tests
were being conducted.
   DeYoung's wife died more than 19 years ago and he cared for his
daughter with devotion and without complaint, neighbors said.
DeYoung said Miss DeYoung would help with the cooking and cleaning.
   ``Ed was always friendly, always joking, and that was unusual
considering what he might have been going through taking care of his
daughter,'' said Ms. Barron.
   ``He was very devoted to her and I know he did it out of love,''
she said.
</TEXT>
