<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0510,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Expresses Shock at U.S.-PLO Talks, Preparing Peace
Initiative</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with protest in Jerusalem, two Cabinet
ministers to raise autonomy issue, RESTORES first reference to
Rabin, NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Saturday he
was shocked by Washington's decision to open a dialogue with the PLO
and announced he was preparing a new peace initiative to counter the
U.S. move.
   In downtown Jerusalem, thousands of right-wing Israelis and
Jewish settlers demonstrated to protest the new U.S. policy. Some
protesters later marched to the U.S. Consulate.
   ``We must break terrorism in the field and the state terrorism of
both the PLO and the United States,'' one speaker told protesters.
   Shamir's comments on Israel radio were the first by the
right-wing leader since Washington announced Wednesday it had ended
a ban on talks with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   ``It's not surprising that we were shocked by the (U.S.) decision
to talk with the organization which is our most radical enemy,'' he
said.
   Shamir said the U.S. move posed ``a very serious test'' to
Israel's alliance with Washington, the strongest supporter of the
Jewish state and the donor of $3 billion a year in foreign aid.
   In making the decision, the United States gave in to external and
internal pressures, Shamir said. He predicted U.S.-PLO dialogue will
fail when PLO chief Yasser Arafat is put to the test of halting
terrorism.
   He reiterated his staunch opposition to any dealings with the PLO.
   Shamir also confirmed earlier reports of his plan to announce a
new Middle East initiative after the formation of Israel's new
government. He declined to elaborate.
   Shamir's close ally in the right-wing Likud bloc, Cabinet
Minister Moshe Arens, said on the radio that Israel's next
government will discuss a unilateral move to grant Palestinians
limited self-rule, as envisioned in the 1978 U.S.-mediated Camp
David accord between Israel and Egypt.
   The PLO says it will settle only for an independent Palestinian
state. Egypt views the accord as outdated.
   Israel radio said two Labor Cabinet Ministers, Gad Yaakobi and
Moshe Shahal, plan to raise the autonomy issue at the Cabinet
meeting Sunday.
   The self-rule idea could bridge the gap between Likud and the
left-of-center Labor Party led by Foreign Minister Shimon Peres.
   The two main parties have been locked in complex coalition talks
since Israel's Nov. 1 parliament elections. They disagree sharply on
the issue of peace moves. Likud opposes conceding land captured in
1967, while Labor favors a territorial compromise in exchange for
peace.
   Peres and other Labor leaders, responding to the recent U.S.
decision to talk to the PLO, have proposed elections in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip and talks with elected
Palestinian representatives as a substitute for the PLO.
   Shamir may include the idea in his autonomy program. Palestinian
notables in the occupied territories, however, reject moves that
would exclude the PLO.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, a Labor Party member, said Friday
the U.S. decision on the PLO was ``a grave mistake, both regarding
terrorism and the possibility of open political talks.''
   The decision, he said, ``actually granted legitimacy to the
uprising in the territories,'' or the yearlong Palestinian revolt in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Since the uprising broke out Dec. 8,
329 Palestinians and 13 Israelis have been killed.
   Demonstrators in front of the U.S. consulate lit candles and
waved signs that read: ``The United States gave a medal to the
killers of our children,'' and ``U.S.A., stay out!''
   The organizers said they later glued to the consulate door a
letter addressed to President Reagan accusing the United States of
``falling to its knees'' before the PLO.
</TEXT>
