<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SoCalQuake     12-17 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SoCal Quake,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mild Earthquake, Centered In Ocean, Shakes Parts Of Southern
California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEAL BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake centered in the
Pacific Ocean south of this coastal community shook Southern
California on Saturday afternoon, but no injury or damage was
reported, officials said.
   The offshore tremor, which measured at 3.4 on the Richter scale,
struck at 3:46 p.m., said Robert Finn a spokesman for the California
Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
   The epicenter was 4 miles south and slightly west of Seal Beach,
about 25 miles southeast of downtown Los Angeles, Finn said.
   ``We've received a few calls with people just inquiring,'' said
police dispatcher Beth Clarke. She said about 15 people called to
report they felt a jolting motion.
   Ms. Clarke said the quake was felt by officers in the station.
``It probably only lasted a couple of seconds,'' she added.
   The tremor also was felt by residents of Long Beach, another
coastal city about 20 miles south of Los Angeles.
   ``We've received about half a dozen calls from the public
reporting a quake,'' said Long Beach police Officer Billy Quach. ``I
did not feel the quake at all.''
</TEXT>
