<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0554 12-17 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0554,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lebanese Militia Frees Three Kidnapped Irish Soldiers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Red Cross planning to restore
full operations; RECASTING to TIGHTEN.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate Lebanese militia on Saturday
surrounded pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists and forced them to
free three Irish U.N. peacekeeping troops kidnapped a day earlier in
south Lebanon.
   Also Saturday, PLO chief Yasser Arafat indicated he was involved
in the release a day earlier of a Swiss Red Cross official. A
leading Shiite cleric said he has given up trying to free 14 other
foreign hostages because his efforts have reached a ``dead end.''
   Lebanese police said the mainstream Shiite Moslem militia Amal
surrounded a house in the village of Sultaniyeh and forced about 20
men inside, belonging to the group Faithful Resistance, to surrender
and free the three Irish soldiers of the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon or UNIFIL.
   A police spokesman said the militia also conducted a sweep
rounding up 80 other members of Faithful Resistance, a small fanatic
affiliate of Hezbollah, or Party of God, which is believed to be the
umbrella organization for pro-Iranian groups holding foreign
hostages in Lebanon.
   Police sources said the Faithful Resistance kidnapped the Irish
soldiers Friday in retaliation for the Israeli detainment of a group
leader and other guerrillas.
   ``Amal summoned the Faithful Resistance's seven commanders
individually to a meeting to discuss the release of the Irish
soldiers and captured them when they refused to release peacekeepers
unconditionally. Their followers gave in a while later,'' said the
police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing
regulations.
   The house in Sultaniyeh was one mile southwest of Tibnin, where
the Irishmen were abducted. The 620-strong Irish batallion serving
with UNIFIL is headquartered in Tibnin, a village 13 miles north of
Israel which borders Israel's six-to-10-mile self-proclaimed
security zone.
   The police spokesman identified the three rescued Irish soldiers
as Corp. Patrick Maeken, 35, Pvt. Brian Kearney, 25, and Pvt. Bernak
McCarugmey, 30.
   UNIFIL spokesman Timur Goksel said Amal returned the three to
their command. ``They are in good shape,'' Goksel said in a
telephone interview.
   The abductions apparently were intended to retaliate for Israel's
seizure Thursday of Faithful Resistance guerrilla commander Jawad
Kasfi in Tibnin.
   The Israeli military command said Kasfi was linked to attacks on
Israeli army forces and an Israeli-backed militia, the South Lebanon
Army, since 1984.
   Red Cross worker Peter Winkler, 32, was freed Friday night in the
southern city of Sidon, where he was abducted Nov. 17. Police said
Winkler boarded a ferry Saturday at the Christian port of Jounieh,
heading for Cyprus. The Swiss Foreign Ministry earlier said Winkler
was to fly home via Cyprus Sunday.
   Arafat indicated Saturday he played a role in the release when he
was in Geneva last week to address the United Nations.
   ``When I was in Geneva, the chief of the Red Cross asked me to
help release the Swiss employee, and he has been released,'' Arafat
said without elaborating. He spoke shortly after his arrival in
Tunis, Tunisia, where the Palestine Liberation Organization is
headquartered.
   In Bern, Swiss Foreign Minister Rene Felber said Saturday that
talks between a Swiss official and Arafat proved ``useful.''
   Felber said Winkler's captors tried to tie his release to a
lenient sentence for a jailed Lebanese plane hijacker, Hussein
Hariri, but Switzerland refused any concessions.
   He said that in indirect contacts, the kidnappers identified
themselves as members of a dissident Palestinian group named
``Organization of Socialist Revolution.''
   An official of the all-Swiss International Committee of the Red
Cross said the humanitarian agency will negotiate safety guarantees
with ``various parties and groups'' in Lebanon before resuming full
activities there.
   The delegation, cut nearly in half after Winkler was kidnapped,
will be brought back to its original size of 30 as soon as possible,
said the official at ICRC headquarters in Geneva, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Winkler's release leaves 14 foreigners, including nine Americans,
missing and presumed kidnapped by pro-Iranian factions in Lebanon.
   Longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent
for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   The Beirut daily Al-Liwaa quoted Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah
Saturday as saying, ``I have suspended my initiative on behalf of
the hostages because it reached a dead end.''
   Fadlallah, the spiritual guide of Hezbollah, did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
