<1ST_LINE>u i AM-QuakeConcert 1stLd-Writethru a0508 12-17 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake Concert, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0508,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rostropovich Joins Charity Concert for Quake Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with concert taking place; no pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet-born cellist Mstislav Rostropovich played in
a charity concert for Armenian earthquake victims Saturday night
after postponing a visit to India to take part in the event.
   ``It was very important for me to take part in this concert,''
the 61-year-old musician said before a last-minute rehearsal with
flutist James Galway, conductor Andre Previn and other musicians who
rearranged their schedules and donated time to perform.
   Prince Charles, heir to the British throne, and his wife,
Princess Diana, attended the sell-out concert at the 2,026-seat
Barbican Hall in London.
   The event was part of an effort called ``Musicians for Armenia,''
which was expected to raise $452,000 from donations worldwide,
including gifts from musicians, concert proceeds and film and
recording rights.
   The British Association of Concert Agents organized the appeal to
aid some of the thousands of survivors from the killer earthquake
Dec. 7 that killed an estimated 55,000 people.
   The Soviet Union and five other nations televised the late-night
performance. The British Broadcasting Corp.'s world service
rearranged its radio programming to allow its estimated audience of
25 million to hear the concert live.
   ``At the moment, with what has happened, I feel that all
Armenians are my relatives,'' said Rostropovich, a U.S. citizen of
Armenian descent who is conductor of the National Symphony Orchestra
in Washington.
   On Friday, Rostropovich, one of the most famous cellists in
history, gave his first solo concert in Britain in nearly two
decades, also in aid of Armenia.
   Previn, who conducted the English Chamber Orchestra during the
concert Saturday, said before the program that it was ``amazing''
the musicians were able to join.
   ``In our business everyone's booked up for the next two or three
years,'' he said. ``It was just good fortune that everyone could
make it at such short notice.''
   ``This terrible catastrophe has provoked the best qualities in
people,'' said Rostropovich.
   The cellist played Villa-Lobos' Bachianas Brasileiras No. 1, then
turned to the piano to accompany his Soviet-born wife, soprano
Galina Vishnevskaya, in works by Tchaikovsky.
   The program also included Galway playing Debussy's Syrinx and
Previn conducting the English Chamber Orchestra in Beethoven's
Coriolan Overture.
   Soviet pianist Andrei Gavrilov, whose family in Armenia escaped
injury in the quake, played Mozart and Chopin.
   The musicians also included violist Yuri Bashmet, pianist Barry
Douglas and violinist Cho-Liang Lin.
   The Times reported that the concert was to be televised in Spain,
the Netherlands, Ireland, Australia, Belgium and the Soviet Union.
   Musicians, organizers, concert hall workers, program printers and
other staff donated their services so that all income could go to
the British Red Cross Armenian Earthquake Appeal fund. Tickets cost
$45, $27 and $18.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
