<DOCNO> AP881217-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-17-88 2139EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Quake-Tents     12-17 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Tents,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Military Plane To Fly Volunteers To Armenia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE RULE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crew planning to take durable, plastic
tents to earthquake victims in Soviet Armenia got word Saturday that
a Soviet military cargo plane will carry them to the disaster site,
the group's leader said.
   The 17-member team is scheduled to leave Sunday, said Anthony
Seraphin, president of Protect-A-Boat and Film Applicators of North
America, the Springfield, Pa., company that came up with the idea
for the quick-to-build shelters.
   ``As far as we know, we're ready to go,'' he said, but added that
he'll ``believe it when we're on the plane.''
   There was no immediate word on when the plane would return to the
Soviet Union with materials it has picked up in other U.S. cities.
   Soviet officials estimate 55,000 lives were lost and 500,000
people were left homeless by the Dec. 7 quake. After hearing of the
massive displacement, Seraphin came up with the idea of using the
film for tents.
   Construction techniques require building frames out of steel and
then shrink-wrapping them with resin-based plastic using a propane
heat gun. Seraphin said a tent that can house 30 people takes about
two hours to build and includes doors, windows and vents.
   The arrival of the Soviet plane would end two days of frustration
for Seraphin and the Washington, D.C.-based Armenia Relief Society.
   ``In the past two days, I would `guesstimate' that we've
contacted close to 100 people from the secretary of state on down to
business people with contacts,'' Seraphin said, adding he had talked
to people in Washington, New York, Detroit, Los Angeles, Maryland
and Florida.
   Earlier in the week, the Air National Guard offered to fly the
group, if Seraphin received permission from the Defense Department.
On Friday, the Defense Department said that the State Department
would have to approve the trip.
   ``Everybody wanted to be very helpful, but no one seemed able to
break through,'' Seraphin said. ``We just had to break through the
red tape.''
   The team intends to go from town to town in the quake area,
building five to 10 shelters and teaching the residents how to build
more for themselves.
   ``Then when we get back, we'll be raising money to send more
material over there so they can do it themselves,'' said Seraphin.
   The group had not made plans for their return as of Saturday.
</TEXT>
