<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama-US 1stLd-Writethru a0600 12-17 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0600,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama's Foreign Minister Says US Will Try To Maintain Military In
Canal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with U.S. reax, PICKS UP 6th
pvs `Noriega, head...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry on Saturday said
the United States is trying to maintain a military presence in
Panama into the next century in spite of the Panama Canal treaties.
   In Washington, a State Department spokesman said the United
States intends to abide by the treaties.
   The Panamanian government statement, issued in Panama City, said:
``The Foreign Ministry has been following the development of a
unilateral thesis in the U.S. State Department under which the
neutrality treaty would allow a limited U.S. military presence in
Panama past Dec. 31, 1999.''
   The Panama Canal treaties, signed by President Carter and
Panamanian leader Omar Torrijos in 1977, stipulate that on Dec. 31,
1999, ``only the Republic of Panama will operate the canal and
maintain military forces, defense sites and military installations
inside national territory.''
   The Panamanian Foreign Ministry said the U.S. intention to remain
in Panama after 1999 is ``one of the main reasons for the economic
aggression and the threatening use of force against Panama.''
   Asked about Panama's charges, State Department spokesman Dennis
Harter in Washington said, ``It's not the first time they've said
anything like that. They've said it fairly frequently.
   ``We intend to abide by the Panama Canal treaties,'' he added in
an interview with The Associated Press. ``We have been and we intend
to continue to.''
   The United States imposed economic sanctions on Panama earlier
this year and expanded its military force along the canal in an
effort to force Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to step down.
   Noriega, head of the armed forces and de facto leader of Panama,
is under U.S. indictment on charges of drug trafficking and money
laundering. He denies the accusations.
   The Foreign Ministry statement alluded to a document issued last
week by Army's Southern Command saying that after 1999 ``the United
States will continue showing its determination to support the
neutrality and operation of the Panama Canal as well as regional and
U.S. security interests.''
   The Southern Command report said the U.S. Defense Department
approved ``a preliminary plan for an orderly, phased withdrawal from
Panama,'' but it did not give specific withdrawal dates. It also
said the Southern Command now operating along the banks of the
Panama Canal will not be eliminated when U.S. military presence ends
in Panama. However, it did not say where the Southern Command will
be located.
   The U.S. Army has about 13,000 troops assigned to the Southern
Command, about 3,000 of whom arrived in March to add pressure on
Noriega.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
