<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FighterDown 1stLd-Writethru a0536 12-17 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fighter Down, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0536,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jet Fighters Crash On Air Station Runway, Pilots OK</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with fighter pulled from water, in one
piece but damaged. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALAMEDA NAVAL AIR STATION, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy F-14 Tomcat jet
fighter landing at Alameda Naval Station crashed into another F-14
on a runway, veering off into the 12-foot deep Oakland Estuary.
   The pilot and a radar officer ejected from the plane Friday
before it hit the water on and were rescued apparently unhurt, but
were hospitalized for possible shock, officials said.
   On Saturday, the fighter was lifted from the waterway, damaged
but in one piece, by a huge crane. It was taken to a nearby pier at
the Alameda Naval Air Station, said Navy spokesman Bill Valente.
Earlier, officials had said they thought the plane had shattered on
impact.
   The $30 million jet, the type featured in the hit movie ``Top
Gun,'' crashed on the north end of the air station's north-south
runway. The air station is located on the eastern side of San
Francisco Bay.
   One crew member was rescued about half an hour later by a passing
tugboat and the second by a Coast Guard rescue boat, said Coast
Guard Lt. Michael Sullivan.
   Two F-14s landed without incident before a third plane struck the
second one and veered into the estuary, Valente said. The planes
were from Miramar Naval Air Station north of San Diego, he added.
   The two crew members in the second plane, which remained on the
runway, walked away from the crash, unhurt, Valente said. The plane
lost part of its right wing, but officials said they hadn't
determined the cost of damage or whether the plane could be repaired.
   The F-14 is a large and powerful aircraft that in 1972 became the
standard fleet fighter aboard aircraft carriers at sea.
   Visible damage to the aircraft after it was pulled from the water
included a missing hatch and part of the nose, officials said.
</TEXT>
